# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: federal-government-of-the-united-states
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p01] The **118th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, composed of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p01] It convened in Washington, D.C., on January 3, 2023, and ended on January 3, 2025, during the final two years of Joe Biden's presidency.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p01] With Republicans winning the House, the 118th Congress ended the federal government trifecta Democrats held in the 117th.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p01] This congress also featured the first female Senate president pro tempore (Patty Murray), the first black party leader (Hakeem Jeffries) in congressional history, and the longest-serving Senate party leaders (Mitch McConnell and Dick Durbin).
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p01] The Senate had the highest number of Independent members in a single Congress since the ratification of the 17th Amendment after Joe Manchin left the Democratic Party to become an Independent.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p01] The 118th Congress was characterized as a uniquely ineffectual Congress, with its most notable events pointing towards political dysfunction.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p01] By August 2024, the Congress has passed only 78 laws, less than a third of the next lowest laws per Congress in the 112th Congress, which also featured a Republican House opposing the Democratic Senate and White House.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p01] This resulted in the need for a legislative coalition to pass key legislation, allowing the minority to exercise powers usually reserved for the majority.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p01] The fractious session demotivated many veteran legislators, with five committee chairs among the dozens who declared their resignation or retirement before the end of the session, three of whom were eligible to reprise their positions if the Republican Party retained their majority for 2025.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p01] A higher-than-average number of retiring lawmakers were those attempting to pass bipartisan and collaborative legislation.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p01] Two complete discharge petitions were filed in late 2024, both Republican-led with majority Democratic support, demonstrating a trend towards bucking leadership and lack of party discipline; such a gambit was last successful in 2015 to support the Export–Import Bank.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p01] The second of these, a bill to remove certain Social Security restrictions, was subject to an unusual legislative procedure when a chair pro forma called forth a motion to table on a bill while the chamber was empty, flouting House convention and agreements.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p01] The Congress began with a multi-ballot election for Speaker of the House, which had not happened since the 68th Congress in 1923.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p01] Kevin McCarthy was eventually elected speaker on the 15th ballot.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p01] After relying on bipartisan votes to get out of a debt ceiling crisis and government shutdown threats, McCarthy became the first speaker ever to be removed from the role during a legislative session on October 3, 2023.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p01] Following three failed attempts by various representatives to fill the post, on October 25, Mike Johnson was elected as speaker.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p01] Johnson would advance four more bipartisan continuing resolutions from November into March to avoid shutdowns.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p01] Congress finalized the 2024 United States federal budget on March 23, 2024, through two separate minibus packages.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p01] Following a contentious foreign-aid vote, a motion to remove Johnson from the speakership was defeated in a bipartisan vote.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p01] Partisan disciplinary actions also increased.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p01] With the expulsion of New York representative George Santos from the House in December 2023, over the opposition of the speaker, this was the first congress since the 107th in which a member was expelled, and the first ever in which a Republican was.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p01] There was also an increase of censures passed in the House, being the first congress with multiple censures since the 1983 congressional page sex scandal and the most in one year since 1870.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p01] In December 2023, House Republicans authorized an impeachment inquiry into Joe Biden, followed by the impeachment of Alejandro Mayorkas in February 2024, the first time a cabinet secretary has been the target of impeachment proceedings since William W.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p01] Belknap in 1876, and only the second such cabinet impeachment in history.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p01] The charges were dismissed by the Senate, the first time the Senate dismissed impeachment articles without trial after the reading.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p01] This is the most recent Congress with Democratic senators from the states of Montana (Jon Tester) and Ohio (Sherrod Brown), both of whom lost re-election in 2024.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p02] The numbers refer to their Senate classes.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p02] All class 3 seats were contested in the November 2022 elections.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p02] In this Congress, class 3 means their term commenced in 2023, requiring re-election in 2028; class 1 means their term ends with this Congress, requiring re-election in 2024; and class 2 means their term began in the last Congress, requiring re-election in 2026.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p02] All 435 seats were filled by election in November 2022.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p02] Additionally, six non-voting members were elected from the American territories and Washington, D.C.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p02] The numbers refer to the congressional district of the given state in this Congress.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/118th-united-states-congress-p02] Eight new congressional districts were created or re-created, while eight others were eliminated, as a result of the 2020 United States census.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] The United States of America is a federal republic consisting of 50 states, a federal district (Washington, D.C., the capital city of the United States), five major territories, and minor islands.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] Both the states and the United States as a whole are each sovereign jurisdictions.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] The Tenth Amendment to the United States Constitution allows states to exercise all powers of government not delegated to the federal government.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] Each state has its own constitution and government.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] All states and their residents are represented in the federal Congress, a bicameral legislature consisting of the Senate and the House of Representatives.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] Each state elects two senators, while representatives are distributed among the states in proportion to the most recent constitutionally mandated decennial census.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] Each state is entitled to select a number of electors to vote in the Electoral College, the body that elects the nation's president and vice president, equal to the total of representatives and senators in Congress from that state.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] The federal district does not have representatives in the Senate, but has a non-voting delegate in the House, and it is entitled to electors in the Electoral College.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] Congress can admit more states, but it cannot create a new state from territory of an existing state or merge two or more states into one without the consent of all states involved.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] Each new state is admitted on an equal footing with the existing states.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] The United States possesses fourteen territories.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] Five of them (American Samoa, Guam, the Northern Mariana Islands, Puerto Rico, and the United States Virgin Islands) have a permanent, non-military population, while nine of them (the United States Minor Outlying Islands) do not.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] With the exception of Navassa Island, Puerto Rico, and the U.S.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] Virgin Islands, which are located in the Caribbean, all territories are located in the Pacific Ocean.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] One territory, Palmyra Atoll, is considered to be incorporated, meaning the full body of the Constitution has been applied to it.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] The other territories are unincorporated, meaning the Constitution does not fully apply to them.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] Ten territories (the Minor Outlying Islands and American Samoa) are considered to be unorganized, meaning they have not had an organic act enacted by Congress.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] The four other territories are organized, meaning an organic act has been enacted by Congress.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] The five inhabited territories each have limited autonomy and territorial legislatures and governors.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] Residents cannot vote in federal elections, although all are represented by non-voting delegates in the House.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] The largest state by population is California, with a population of 39,538,223 people.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] The smallest is Wyoming, with a population of 576,851 people.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] The federal district has a larger population (689,545) than both Wyoming and Vermont.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] The largest state by area is Alaska, encompassing 665,384 square miles (1,723,340 km2).
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] The smallest is Rhode Island, encompassing 1,545 square miles (4,000 km2).
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] The most recent states to be admitted, Alaska and Hawaii, were admitted in 1959.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] The largest territory by population is Puerto Rico, with a population of 3,285,874 people, larger than 21 states.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] The smallest is the Northern Mariana Islands, with a population of 47,329 people.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] Puerto Rico is the largest territory by area, encompassing 5,325 square miles (13,790 km2).
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/50-states] The smallest territory, Kingman Reef, encompasses 0.005 square miles (0.013 km2), or a little larger than 3 acres.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-more-perfect-union-film] The film depicts events surrounding creation of the United States Constitution, and is focused mainly on James Madison, who wrote most of that document and took extensive notes during the convention's discussions and proceedings.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-more-perfect-union-film] The period immediately following the American Revolutionary War was marked by intense political unrest, owing to huge debts, the interruption of trade and business, shortages of labor, and personal turmoils, all created by the War.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-more-perfect-union-film] It soon became evident that the Articles of Confederation were insufficient to address the country's needs.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-more-perfect-union-film] A movement soon emerged to upgrade or replace the Articles, and Madison was foremost in the movement.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-more-perfect-union-film] However, he needed the support of George Washington, and needed to show that a new government would be sufficient to address such challenges as Shays' Rebellion and the growing trade problems between the independent States.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-more-perfect-union-film] Madison was strongly opposed by those who feared a strong central government, people known either as *States Rights Advocates* or as *Anti-Federalists*, such as Roger Sherman and John Dickinson.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-more-perfect-union-film] Madison was in favor of a bicameral congress, and envisioned each house being elected with seats allocated to states in proportion to population.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-more-perfect-union-film] In this he was opposed by the States Rights Advocates, and he eventually accepted the compromises necessary to address their concerns.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-more-perfect-union-film] The film highlights the basis for these compromises.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-more-perfect-union-film] The film also depicts the convention delegates' debate about the slave trade.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-more-perfect-union-film] The movie was filmed on location at Independence Hall in Philadelphia, in Williamsburg, Virginia, and at other historical sites.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-more-perfect-union-film] Much of the film is shot from the viewpoint of James Madison, with the script being based primarily on his writings.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/a-more-perfect-union-film] These include the copious minutes he took during the Constitutional Convention, which were published after his death as *Notes of Debates in the Federal Convention of 1787*.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The anti-slavery movement originated during the Age of Enlightenment, focused on ending the transatlantic slave trade.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In Colonial America, a few German Quakers issued the 1688 Germantown Quaker Petition Against Slavery, which marked the beginning of the American abolitionist movement.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Before the Revolutionary War, evangelical colonists were the primary advocates for the opposition to slavery and the slave trade, doing so on the basis of humanitarian ethics.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Still, others such as James Oglethorpe, the founder of the colony of Georgia, also retained political motivations for the removal of slavery.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Prohibiting slavery through the 1735 Georgia Experiment in part to prevent Spanish partnership with Georgia's runaway slaves, Oglethorpe eventually revoked the act in 1750 after the Spanish's defeat in the Battle of Bloody Marsh eight years prior.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] During the Revolutionary era, all states abolished the international slave trade, but South Carolina reversed its decision.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Between the Revolutionary War and 1804, laws, constitutions, or court decisions in each of the Northern states provided for the gradual or immediate abolition of slavery.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] No Southern state adopted similar policies.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1807, Congress made the importation of slaves a crime, effective January 1, 1808, which was as soon as Article I, section 9 of the Constitution allowed.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] A small but dedicated group, under leaders such as William Lloyd Garrison and Frederick Douglass, agitated for abolition in the mid-19th century.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] John Brown became an advocate and militia leader in attempting to end slavery by force of arms.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the Civil War, immediate emancipation became a war goal for the Union in 1863 and was fully achieved in 1865.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] American abolitionism began well before the United States was founded as a nation.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1652, Rhode Island made it illegal for any person, black or white, to be "bound" longer than ten years.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The law, however, was widely ignored, and Rhode Island became involved in the slave trade in 1700.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] An early prominent example of resistance by enslaved people occurred during Bacon's Rebellion in 1676.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Occurring in Virginia, the rebellion saw European indentured servants and African people (of indentured, enslaved, and free negroes) band together against William Berkeley because of his refusal to fully remove Native American tribes in the region.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] At the time, Native Americans in the region were hosting raids against lower-class settlers encroaching on their land after the Third Powhatan War (1644–1646), which left many white and black indentured servants and slaves without a sense of protection from their government.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Led by Nathaniel Bacon, the unification that occurred between the white lower class and blacks during this rebellion was perceived as dangerous and thus was quashed with the implementation of the Virginia Slave Codes of 1705.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Still, this event introduced the premise that blacks and whites could work together towards the goal of self-liberation, which became increasingly prevalent as abolition gained traction within America.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The first written statement against slavery in Colonial America was prepared in 1688 by members of the Religious Society of Friends.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The intention of the petition was to stop slavery within the Quaker community, where 70% of Quakers owned slaves between 1681 and 1705.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] It acknowledged the universal rights of all people.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] While the Quaker establishment did not take action at that time, the unusually early, clear, and forceful argument in the petition initiated the spirit that finally led to the end of slavery in the Society of Friends (1776) and in the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania (1780).
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Quaker Quarterly Meeting of Chester, Pennsylvania, made its first protest in 1711.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Within a few decades the entire slave trade was under attack, being opposed by such Quaker leaders as William Burling, Benjamin Lay, Ralph Sandiford, William Southby, John Woolman, and Anthony Benezet.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Benezet was particularly influential, inspiring a later generation of notable anti-slavery activists, including Granville Sharp, John Wesley, Thomas Clarkson, Olaudah Equiano, Benjamin Franklin, Benjamin Rush, Absalom Jones, and Bishop Richard Allen, among others.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Samuel Sewall, a prominent Bostonian, wrote *The Selling of Joseph* (1700) in protest of the widening practice of outright slavery as opposed to indentured servitude in the colonies.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This is the earliest-recorded anti-slavery tract published in the future United States.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Slavery was banned in the colony of Georgia soon after its founding in 1733.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The colony's founder, James Edward Oglethorpe, fended off repeated attempts by South Carolina merchants and land speculators to introduce slavery into the colony.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] His motivations included tactical defense against Spanish collusion with runaway slaves, and prevention of Georgia's largely reformed criminal population from replicating South Carolina's planter class structure.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1737, Quaker abolitionist Benjamin Lay published *All Slave-Keepers That Keep the Innocent in Bondage, Apostates*, which was printed by his friend, Benjamin Franklin.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The event resulted in 25 colonists and 35 to 50 African slaves killed, as well as the implementation of the 1740 Negro Act to prevent another slave uprising.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In her book, "The Slave's Cause" by Manisha Sinha, Sinha considers the Stono Rebellion to be an important act of abolition from the perspective of the slave, recognizing their agency and subsequent humanity as cause for self-liberation.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The struggle between Georgia and South Carolina led to the first debates in Parliament over the issue of slavery, occurring between 1740 and 1742.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Rhode Island Quakers, associated with Moses Brown, were among the first in America to free slaves.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Benjamin Rush was another leader, as were many Quakers.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] John Woolman gave up most of his business in 1756 to devote himself to campaigning against slavery along with other Quakers.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Between 1764 and 1774, seventeen enslaved African Americans appeared before the Massachusetts courts in freedom suits, spurred on the decision made in the *Somerset v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Stewart* case, which although not applying the colonies was still received positively by American abolitionists.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Boston lawyer Benjamin Kent represented them.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Whipple*) to liberate Jenny Slew, a mixed-race woman who had been kidnapped in Massachusetts and then handled as a slave.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] According to historian Steven Pincus, many of the colonial legislatures worked to enact laws that would limit slavery.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Provincial legislature of Massachusetts Bay, as noted by historian Gary B.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Nash, approved a law "prohibiting the importation and purchase of slaves by any Massachusetts citizen." The Loyalist governor of Massachusetts, Thomas Hutchinson, vetoed the law, an action that prompted angered reaction from the general public.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] American abolitionists were cheered by the decision in *Somerset v Stewart* (1772), which prohibited slavery in the United Kingdom, though not in its colonies.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1774, the influential Fairfax Resolves called for an end to the "wicked, cruel and unnatural" Atlantic slave trade.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] One of the first articles advocating the emancipation of slaves and the abolition of slavery was written by Thomas Paine.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Titled "African Slavery in America", it appeared on 8 March 1775 in the *Postscript to the Pennsylvania Journal and Weekly Advertiser*.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Society for the Relief of Free Negroes Unlawfully Held in Bondage (Pennsylvania Abolition Society) was the first American abolition society, formed 14 April 1775, in Philadelphia, primarily by Quakers.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The society suspended operations during the American Revolutionary War and was reorganized in 1784, with Benjamin Franklin as its first president.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1777, the Vermont Republic became the first independent state in North America to prohibit slavery: slaves were not directly freed, but masters were required to remove slaves from Vermont.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Constitution included several provisions which accommodated slavery, although none used the word.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Passed unanimously by the Congress of the Confederation in 1787, the Northwest Ordinance forbade slavery in the Northwest Territory, a vast area (the future Ohio, Indiana, Illinois, Michigan, and Wisconsin) in which slavery had been legal, but population was sparse.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The first state to begin a gradual abolition of slavery was Pennsylvania, in 1780.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] All importation of slaves was prohibited, but none were freed at first, only the slaves of masters who failed to register them with the state, along with the "future children" of enslaved mothers.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Those enslaved in Pennsylvania before the 1780 law went into effect were not freed until 1847.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Massachusetts took a much more radical position.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1780, during the Revolution, Massachusetts ratified its constitution and included within it a clause that declared all men equal.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Based upon this clause, several freedom suits were filed by enslaved African Americans living in Massachusetts.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1783, its Supreme Court, in the case of *Commonwealth v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Nathaniel Jennison*, reaffirmed the case of *Brom and Bett v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Ashley*, which held that even slaves were people who had a constitutional right to liberty.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This gave freedom to slaves, effectively abolishing slavery.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] States with a greater economic interest in slaves, such as New York and New Jersey, passed gradual emancipation laws.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] While some of these laws were gradual, these states enacted the first abolition laws in the entire "New World".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the State of New York, the enslaved population was transformed into indentured servants before being granted full emancipation in 1827.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In other states, abolitionist legislation provided freedom only for the children of the enslaved.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In New Jersey, slavery was not fully prohibited until the passage of the Thirteenth Amendment.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] All of the other states north of Maryland began gradual abolition of slavery between 1781 and 1804, based on the Pennsylvania model and by 1804, all the Northern states had passed laws to gradually or immediately abolish it.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some slaves continued in involuntary, unpaid "indentured servitude" for two more decades, and others were moved south and sold to new owners in slave states.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some individual slaveholders, particularly in the upper South, freed slaves, sometimes in their wills.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Many noted they had been moved by the revolutionary ideals of the equality of men.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The number of free blacks as a proportion of the black population in the upper South increased from less than 1 percent to nearly 10 percent between 1790 and 1810 as a result of these actions.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some slave owners, concerned about the increase in free blacks, which they viewed as destabilizing, freed slaves on condition that they emigrate to Africa.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] All U.S. states abolished the transatlantic slave trade by 1798.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] South Carolina, which had abolished the slave trade in 1787, reversed that decision in 1803.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the American South, freedom suits were rejected by the courts, which held that the rights in the state constitutions did not apply to African Americans.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The institution of slavery remained solid in the South, and that region's customs and social beliefs evolved into a strident defense of slavery in response to the rise of a growing anti-slavery stance in the North.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1835 alone, abolitionists mailed over a million pieces of anti-slavery literature to the South, giving rise to the gag rules in Congress, after the theft of mail from the Charleston, South Carolina, post office, and much back-and-forth about whether postmasters were required to deliver this mail.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] According to the Postmaster General, they were not.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Under the Constitution, the importation of enslaved persons could not be prohibited until 1808 (20 years).
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] As the end of the 20 years approached, an Act Prohibiting Importation of Slaves sailed through Congress with little opposition.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] President Jefferson signed it, and it went effect on January 1, 1808.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1820, the Act to Protect the Commerce of the United States and Punish the Crime of Piracy was passed.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This law made importing slaves into the United States a death penalty offense.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1830, most Americans were, at least in principle, opposed to slavery.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, opponents of slavery deliberated on how to end the institution, as well as what would become of the slaves once they were free.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the 1830s there was a progressive shift in thinking in the North.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Mainstream opinion changed from gradual emancipation and resettlement of freed blacks in Africa, sometimes a condition of their manumission, to immediatism: freeing all the slaves immediately and sorting out the problems later.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This change was in many cases sudden, a consequence of the individual's coming in direct contact with the horrors of American slavery, or hearing of them from a credible source.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The American beginning of abolitionism as a political movement is usually dated from 1 January 1831, when Wm.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Lloyd Garrison (as he always signed himself) published the first issue of his new weekly newspaper, *The Liberator* (1831), which appeared without interruption until slavery in the United States was abolished in 1865, when it closed.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Abolitionists included those who joined the American Anti-Slavery Society or its auxiliary groups in the 1830s and 1840s, as the movement fragmented.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The fragmented anti-slavery movement included groups such as the Liberty Party; the American and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society; the American Missionary Association; and the Church Anti-Slavery Society.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Historians traditionally distinguish between moderate anti-slavery reformers or gradualists, who concentrated on stopping the spread of slavery, and radical abolitionists or immediatists, whose demands for unconditional emancipation often merged with a concern for Black civil rights.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Nearly all Northern politicians, such as Abraham Lincoln, rejected the "immediate emancipation" called for by the abolitionists, seeing it as "extreme".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Indeed, many Northern leaders, including Lincoln, Stephen Douglas (the Democratic nominee in 1860), John C.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Frémont (the Republican nominee in 1856), and Ulysses S.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Grant married into slave-owning Southern families without any moral qualms.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Anti-slavery as a principle was far more than just the wish to prevent the expansion of slavery.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] After 1840, abolitionists rejected this because it let sin continue to exist; they demanded that slavery end everywhere, immediately and completely.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] John Brown was the only abolitionist to have actually planned a violent insurrection, though David Walker promoted the idea.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The abolitionist movement was strengthened by the activities of free African Americans, especially in the Black church, who argued that the old Biblical justifications for slavery contradicted the New Testament.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] African-American activists and their writings were rarely heard outside the Black community.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, they were tremendously influential on a few sympathetic white people, most prominently the first white activist to reach prominence, Wm.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Lloyd Garrison, who was its most effective propagandist.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Garrison's efforts to recruit eloquent spokesmen led to the discovery of ex-slave Frederick Douglass, who eventually became a prominent activist in his own right.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Eventually, Douglass would publish his own widely distributed abolitionist newspaper, *North Star*.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the early 1850s, the American abolitionist movement split into two camps over the question of whether the United States Constitution did or did not protect slavery.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This issue arose in the late 1840s after the publication of *The Unconstitutionality of Slavery* by Lysander Spooner.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Garrisonians, led by Garrison and Wendell Phillips, publicly burned copies of the Constitution, called it a pact with slavery, and demanded its abolition and replacement.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Another camp, led by Lysander Spooner, Gerrit Smith, and eventually Douglass, considered the Constitution to be an anti-slavery document.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Using an argument based upon Natural Law and a form of social contract theory, they said that slavery fell outside the Constitution's scope of legitimate authority and therefore should be abolished.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Another split in the abolitionist movement was along class lines.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The artisan republicanism of Robert Dale Owen and Frances Wright stood in stark contrast to the politics of prominent elite abolitionists such as industrialist Arthur Tappan and his evangelist brother Lewis.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] While the former pair opposed slavery on a basis of solidarity of "wage slaves" with "chattel slaves", the Whiggish Tappans strongly rejected this view, opposing the characterization of Northern workers as "slaves" in any sense.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Many American abolitionists took an active role in opposing slavery by supporting the Underground Railroad.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This was made illegal by the federal Fugitive Slave Law of 1850, arguably the most hated and most openly evaded federal legislation in the nation's history.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Nevertheless, participants like Harriet Tubman, Henry Highland Garnet, Alexander Crummell, Amos Noë Freeman, and others continued with their work.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Abolitionists were particularly active in Ohio, where some worked directly in the Underground Railroad.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Since only the Ohio River separated free Ohio from slave Kentucky, it was a popular destination for fugitive slaves.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Supporters helped them there, in many cases to cross Lake Erie by boat, into Canada.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Western Reserve area of northeast Ohio was "probably the most intensely antislavery section of the country." The Oberlin-Wellington Rescue got national publicity.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Abolitionist John Brown grew up in Hudson, Ohio.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the South, members of the abolitionist movement or other people opposing slavery were often targets of lynch mob violence before the American Civil War.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] His fellow Duffield Street residents Thomas and Harriet Truesdell were leading members of the abolitionist movement.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Truesdell was a founding member of the Providence Anti-slavery Society before moving to Brooklyn in 1838.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Harriet Truesdell was also very active in the movement, organizing an anti-slavery convention in Pennsylvania Hall (Philadelphia).
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Another prominent Brooklyn-based abolitionist was Rev.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Joshua Leavitt, trained as a lawyer at Yale, who stopped practicing law in order to attend Yale Divinity School, and subsequently edited the abolitionist newspaper *The Emancipator* and campaigned against slavery, as well as advocating other social reforms.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1841, Leavitt published *The Financial Power of Slavery*, which argued that the South was draining the national economy due to its reliance on enslaved workers.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2007, Duffield Street was given the name Abolitionist Place, and the Truesdells' home at 227 Duffield received landmark status in 2021.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This was a direct result of the Union victory in the American Civil War.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The central issue of the war was slavery.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the North, most opponents of slavery supported other modernizing reform movements such as the temperance movement, public schooling, and prison- and asylum-building.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] They were split on the issue of women's activism and their political role, and this contributed to a major rift in the Society.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1839, brothers Arthur Tappan and Lewis Tappan left the Society and formed the American and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society, which did not admit women.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Other members of the Society, including Charles Turner Torrey, Amos Phelps, Henry Stanton, and Alanson St.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Clair, in addition to disagreeing with Garrison on the women's issue, urged taking a much more activist approach to abolitionism and consequently challenged Garrison's leadership at the Society's annual meeting in January 1839.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] When the challenge was beaten back, they left and founded the New Organization, which adopted a more activist approach to freeing slaves.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Soon after, in 1840, they formed the Liberty Party, which had as its sole platform the abolition of slavery.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] By the end of 1840, Garrison himself announced the formation of a third new organization, the Friends of Universal Reform, with sponsors and founding members including prominent reformers Maria Chapman, Abby Kelley Foster, Oliver Johnson, and Bronson Alcott (father of Louisa May Alcott).
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Abolitionists such as William Lloyd Garrison repeatedly condemned slavery for contradicting the principles of freedom and equality on which the country was founded.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The most influential abolitionist publication was *Uncle Tom's Cabin* (1852), the best-selling novel by Harriet Beecher Stowe, who had attended the anti-slavery debates at Lane, of which her father, Lyman Beecher, was the president.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Outraged by the Fugitive Slave Law of 1850 (which made the escape narrative part of everyday news), Stowe emphasized the horrors that abolitionists had long claimed about slavery.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Her depiction of the evil slave owner Simon Legree, a transplanted Yankee who kills the Christ-like Uncle Tom, outraged the North, helped sway British public opinion against the South, and inflamed Southern slave owners who tried to refute it by showing that some slave owners were humanitarian.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] It inspired numerous anti-Tom, pro-slavery novels, several written and published by women.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] According to a book reviewer, "Next to *Uncle Tom's Cabin* (1852), Hinton Helper's critique of slavery and the Southern class system, *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857), was arguably the most important antislavery book of the 1850s." According to historian George M.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Two diametrically opposed anti-slavery positions emerged regarding the United States Constitution.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Garrisonians emphasized that the document permitted and protected slavery and was therefore "an agreement with hell" that had to be rejected in favor of immediate emancipation.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The mainstream anti-slavery position adopted by the new Republican party argued that the Constitution could and should be used to eventually end slavery.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] They assumed that the Constitution gave the government no authority to abolish slavery directly.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, there were multiple tactics available to support the long-term strategy of using the Constitution as a battering ram against the peculiar institution.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] First Congress could block the admission of any new slave states.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] That would steadily move the balance of power in Congress and the Electoral College in favor of freedom.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Congress could abolish slavery in the District of Columbia and the territories.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Congress could use the Commerce Clause to end the interstate slave trade, thereby crippling the steady movement of slavery from the southeast to the southwest.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Congress could recognize free blacks as full citizens and insist on due process rights to protect fugitive slaves from being captured and returned to bondage.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Finally, the government could use patronage powers to promote the anti-slavery cause across the country, especially in the border states.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Pro-slavery elements considered the Republican strategy to be much more dangerous to their cause than radical abolitionism.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Lincoln's election was met by secession.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Indeed, the Republican strategy mapped the "crooked path to abolition" that prevailed during the Civil War.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the 1850s, the slave trade remained legal in all 16 states of the American South.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] While slavery was fading away in the cities and border states, it remained strong in plantation areas that grew cash crops such as cotton, sugar, rice, tobacco or hemp.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] By the 1860 United States census, the slave population in the United States had grown to four million.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] American abolitionism, after Nat Turner's revolt ended its discussion in the South, was based in the North, and white Southerners alleged it fostered slave rebellion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The white abolitionist movement in the North was led by social reformers, especially William Lloyd Garrison, founder of the American Anti-Slavery Society, and writers such as John Greenleaf Whittier and Harriet Beecher Stowe.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Black activists included former slaves such as Frederick Douglass, and free blacks such as the brothers Charles Henry Langston and John Mercer Langston, who helped to found the Ohio Anti-Slavery Society.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some abolitionists said that slavery was criminal and a sin; they also criticized slave owners for using black women as concubines and taking sexual advantage of them.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Compromise of 1850 attempted to resolve issues surrounding slavery caused by the War with Mexico and the admission to the Union of the slave Republic of Texas.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Compromise of 1850 was proposed by "The Great Compromiser" Henry Clay; support was coordinated by Senator Stephen A.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Fugitive Slave Law was a concession to the South.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Abolitionists were outraged, because the new law required Northerners to help in the capture and return of runaway slaves.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1854, Congress passed the Kansas–Nebraska Act, which opened those territories to slavery if the local residents voted that way.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The anti-slavery gains made in previous compromises were reversed.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] A firestorm of outrage brought together former Whigs, Know-Nothings, and former Free Soil Democrats to form a new party in 1854–56, the Republican Party.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] It included a program of rapid modernization involving the government promotion of industry, railroads, banks, free homesteads, and colleges, all to the annoyance of the South.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The new party denounced the Slave Power – that is the political power of the slave owners who supposedly controlled the national government for their own benefit and to the disadvantage of the ordinary white man.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Republicans wanted to achieve the gradual extinction of slavery by market forces, because its members believed that free labor was superior to slave labor.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Southern leaders said the Republican policy of blocking the expansion of slavery into the West made them second-class citizens, and challenged their autonomy.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] With the 1860 presidential victory of Abraham Lincoln, seven Deep South states whose economy was based on cotton and slavery decided to secede and form a new nation.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The American Civil War broke out in April 1861 with the firing on Fort Sumter in South Carolina.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] When Lincoln called for troops to suppress the rebellion, four more slave states seceded.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The crisis in Kansas Territory and the neighboring slave state of Missouri turned bloody during what was known as the Bleeding Kansas crisis of the 1850s.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Proslavery *border ruffians* and *Bushwhackers* fought antislavery "free-staters" and *Jayhawkers*.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Paramilitary guerrilla warfare became widespread in the area, as a prelude to the Civil War.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The violence would spread to many other places, including the Senate Chamber of the U.S.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Capitol where a Southern Democrat attacked a Northern Republican with a cane as his political allies watched.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Explorer, army veteran, and abolitionist John C.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Frémont ran as the first Republican nominee for president in 1856.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The new party crusaded on the slogan: "Free soil, free silver, free men, Frémont and victory!" Although he lost, the party showed a strong base.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] It dominated in Yankee areas of New England, New York and the northern Midwest, and had a strong presence in the rest of the North.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] It had almost no support in the South, where it was roundly denounced in 1856–60 as a divisive force that threatened civil war.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The newly-formed Republican Party gained quite a standing in the 1856 to 1857 election cycle in the U.S.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] House and Senate, cementing its status as the primary party for abolitionists and northerners for some time.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Without using the term "containment", the new Party in the mid-1850s proposed a system of containing slavery once it gained control of the national government.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Militant abolitionists demanded *immediate* emancipation, not a slow-acting containment.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some rejected the new party, and in turn its leaders reassured voters they were not trying to abolish slavery in the U.S. altogether, which was politically impossible, and were just working against its spread.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] John Brown has been called "the most controversial of all 19th-century Americans".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Whereas Garrison was a pacifist, Brown believed violence was unfortunately necessary to end slavery.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The raid, though unsuccessful in the short term, may have helped Lincoln get elected and moved the Southern states to secede, leading to the Civil War.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some historians regard Brown as a crazed lunatic, while David S.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Reynolds hails him as the man who "killed slavery, sparked the civil war, and seeded civil rights".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] His raid in October 1859 involved a band of 22 men who seized the Federal armory at Harper's Ferry, Virginia (since 1863, West Virginia), knowing it contained tens of thousands of weapons.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Brown believed the South was on the verge of a gigantic slave uprising and that one spark would set it off.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Brown's supporters George Luther Stearns, Franklin B.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Sanborn, Thomas Wentworth Higginson, Theodore Parker, Samuel Gridley Howe, and Gerrit Smith were all abolitionists, members of the so-called Secret Six who provided financial backing for Brown's raid.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Brown's raid, says historian David Potter, "was meant to be of vast magnitude and to produce a revolutionary slave uprising throughout the South".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Brown hoped to have quickly a small army of runaway slaves, but made no provision to inform these potential runaways, although he got a little local support.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Army was dispatched to put down the raid, and Brown was quickly captured.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] He was tried for treason against the Commonwealth of Virginia, murder, and inciting a slave revolt, was found guilty of all charges, and was hanged.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] At his trial, Brown exuded a remarkable zeal and single-mindedness that played directly to Southerners' worst fears.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Under Virginia law there was a month between the sentencing and the hanging, and in those weeks Brown spoke gladly with reporters and anyone else who wanted to see him, and wrote many letters.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Few individuals did more to cause secession than John Brown, because Southerners believed he was right about an impending slave revolt.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The day of his execution, Brown prophesied, "the crimes of this guilty land will never be purged away but with blood.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The American Civil War began with the stated goal of preserving the Union, and Lincoln said repeatedly that on the topic of slavery, he was only opposed to its spread to the Western territories.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This view of the war progressively changed, one step at a time, as public sentiment evolved, until by 1865 the war was seen in the North as primarily concerned with ending slavery.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The first federal act taken against slavery during the war occurred on 16 April 1862, when Lincoln signed the District of Columbia Compensated Emancipation Act, which abolished slavery in Washington, D.C.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] A few months later, on June 19, Congress banned slavery in all federal territories, fulfilling Lincoln's 1860 campaign promise.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Meanwhile, the Union suddenly found itself dealing with a steady stream of thousands of escaped slaves, achieving freedom, or so they hoped, by crossing Union lines.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In response, Congress passed the Confiscation Acts, which essentially declared escaped slaves from the South to be confiscated war property, and thus did not have to be returned to their Confederate owners.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation, effective 1 January 1863, which declared only those slaves in Confederate states to be free.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The United States Colored Troops began operations in 1863.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Fugitive Slave Act of 1850 was repealed in June 1864.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Eventually support for abolition was enough to pass the Thirteenth Amendment, ratified in December 1865, which abolished slavery everywhere in the United States, freeing more than 50,000 people still enslaved in Kentucky and Delaware, in 1865 the only states in which slavery still existed.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Thirteenth Amendment also abolished slavery among the Native American tribes.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The abolitionist movement began about the time of the United States' independence.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The first abolition organization was the Pennsylvania Abolition Society, which first met in 1775; Benjamin Franklin was its president.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The New York Manumission Society was founded in 1785 by powerful politicians: John Jay, Alexander Hamilton, and Aaron Burr.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] There is quite a bit of confusion about when slavery was abolished in the Northern states, because "abolishing slavery" meant different things in different states.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] These included the first abolition laws in the entire New World: the Massachusetts Constitution, adopted in 1780, declared all men to have rights, making slavery unenforceable, and it disappeared through the individual actions of both masters and slaves.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, what the abolition forces passed in 1799 in New York State was an Act for the *gradual* abolition of slavery.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Slavery in New York did not officially end until 1827, and more than 70 enslaved people in New York appeared on the 1830 decennial census.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] No slaves appeared in the state's 1840 census.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] New Jersey abolished slavery in 1804, but in 1860 a dozen black people were still held as "perpetual apprentices".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the Northwest Ordinance of 1787, the Congress of the Confederation prohibited slavery in the territories northwest of the Ohio River.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] At the Constitutional Convention of 1787, slavery was the most contentious topic.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Outright prohibition of slavery was impossible, because the Southern states (Georgia, South Carolina, North Carolina, Virginia, Maryland, and Delaware) would never have agreed to it.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The only restriction on slavery that was agreed to was to allow Congress to prohibit the importation of slaves, and even that was postponed for 20 years.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] By that time, all the states except South Carolina had laws abolishing or severely limiting the importation of slaves.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] As he put it, this would "withdraw the citizens of the United States from all further participation in those violations of human rights...which the morality, the reputation, and the best of our country have long been eager to proscribe".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, about 1,000 slaves per year continued to be illegally brought (smuggled) into the United States; see Wanderer and Clotilda.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This was primarily via Spanish Florida and the Gulf Coast; the United States acquired Florida from Spain in 1819, effective 1821, in part as a slave-control measure: no imports coming in, and certainly no fugitives escaping into a refuge.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Congress declined to pass any restriction on the lucrative interstate slave trade, which expanded to replace the supply of African slaves (see Slavery in the United States#Slave trade).
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] After 1776, Quaker and Moravian advocates helped persuade numerous slaveholders in the Upper South to free their slaves.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Manumissions increased for nearly two decades.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Many individual acts by slaveholders freed thousands of slaves.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Slaveholders freed slaves in such numbers that the percentage of free black people in the Upper South increased from 1 to 10 percent, with most of that increase in Virginia, Maryland and Delaware.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] By 1810 three-quarters of blacks in Delaware were free.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The most notable of men offering freedom was Robert Carter III of Virginia, who freed more than 450 people by "Deed of Gift", filed in 1791.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This number was more slaves than any single American had freed before or after.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Often slaveholders came to their decisions by their own struggles in the Revolution; their wills and deeds frequently cited language about the equality of men supporting the decision to set slaves free.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The era's changing economy also encouraged slaveholders to release slaves.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Planters were shifting from labor-intensive tobacco to mixed-crop cultivation and needed fewer slaves.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] By 1860, 91.7% of the blacks in Delaware and 49.7% of those in Maryland were free.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Such early free families often formed the core of artisans, professionals, preachers, and teachers in future generations.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, this did not signal racial equality.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Though free from slavery, blacks still faced immense discrimination.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] For example, Delaware affirmed and reaffirmed black disenfranchisement several times throughout the late 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Delaware's General Assembly enacted harsh black codes throughout the 19th century that restricted travel, property ownership, expression, and socialization for African Americans.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The amendment failed and Missouri became a slave state.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] According to historian David Brion Davis, this may have been the first time in the world that a political leader openly attacked slavery's perceived legality in such a radical manner.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Postmaster General refused to allow the mails to carry abolition pamphlets to the South.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Northern teachers suspected of abolitionism were expelled from the South, and abolitionist literature was banned.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] One Northerner, Amos Dresser (1812–1904), in 1835 was tried in Nashville, Tennessee, for possessing anti-slavery publications, convicted, and as punishment was whipped publicly.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Southerners rejected the denials of Republicans that they were abolitionists.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] They pointed to John Brown's attempt in 1859 to start a slave uprising as proof that multiple Northern conspiracies were afoot to ignite slave rebellions.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Although some abolitionists did call for slave revolts, no evidence of any other Brown-like conspiracy has been discovered.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The North felt threatened as well, for as Eric Foner concludes, "northerners came to view slavery as the very antithesis of the good society, as well as a threat to their own fundamental values and interests".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The famous, "fiery" abolitionist Abby Kelley Foster, from Massachusetts, was considered an "ultra" abolitionist who believed in full civil rights for all black people.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] She held to the view that the freed slaves would colonize Liberia.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Parts of the anti-slavery movement became known as "Abby Kellyism".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] She recruited Susan B Anthony and Lucy Stone to the movement.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Effingham Capron, a cotton and textile scion, who attended the Quaker meeting where Abby Kelley Foster and her family were members, became a prominent abolitionist at the local, state, and national levels.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The local anti-slavery society at Uxbridge, Massachusetts, had more than 25% of the town's population as members.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] McPherson in 1964 defined an abolitionist "as one who before the Civil War had agitated for the immediate, unconditional and total abolition of slavery in the United States".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He notes that many historians have used a broader definition without his emphasis on immediacy.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Thus he does not include opponents of slavery such as Abraham Lincoln or the Republican Party; they called for the immediate end to expansion of slavery before 1861.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] As such, abolitionism in the United States was identified by historians as an expression of moralism, it often operated in tandem with another social reform effort, the temperance movement.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Slavery was also attacked, to a lesser degree, as harmful on economic grounds.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Evidence was that the South, with many enslaved African Americans on plantations, was definitely poorer than the North, which had few.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Historians and scholars have largely overlooked the work of black abolitionists; instead, they have focused on only a few black abolitionists, such as Frederick Douglass.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Yet lesser-known black abolitionists, such as Martin Delany and James Monroe Whitfield, also played an undeniably large role in shaping the movement.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black abolitionists had the distinct problem of having to confront an often-hostile American public, while still acknowledging their nationality and struggle.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] As a result, many black abolitionists "intentionally adopted aspects of British, New England, and Midwestern cultures".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Furthermore, much of abolitionist rhetoric, and black abolitionist rhetoric in particular, were influenced by the Puritan preaching heritage.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Frederick Douglass was a notable black abolitionist, who significantly contributed to the transnational abolitionist movement through his lecture tours of the United Kingdom from 1845 to 1847.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In particular, he had a connection with Daniel O'Connell: Both O'Connell and Douglass strongly opposed slavery.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] On 4 October 1845, the British and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society gave Douglass a Bible bound in gold.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] African Americans, with Douglass being a key example, were involving themselves in US foreign relations and influencing British anti-slavery rhetoric.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Douglass was best known for his speeches, and he completed 280 lectures across the UK and Ireland in the 19 months that he was there.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black abolitionist rhetoric discussed relationships between power, race, and the popular imagination, showing the complexities of the morality and representation of the abolitionist debate.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Douglass and other black nationalists capitalised on pre-existing political and ideological debates among the UK to reassert the need for abolitionism.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In general, Black female abolitionists had separate motives and rhetorical strategies than White female abolitionists.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They were often middle class and members of literary societies; the ones to which they belonged were often made up of solely Black women.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In their activist efforts, they held themselves to high moral standards to be viewed as legitimate by others.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Sarah Mapps Douglass, a free-born Quaker who wrote articles for *The Liberator* on abolition also served as the secretary for a literary society for women in Philadelphia, where she emphasized the importance of education and morality for Black women.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black women that escaped slavery would sometimes write and publish their slave narratives as a way to argue for abolition.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In opposition to male slave narratives, like Frederick Douglass's, which highlighted literacy, Black women emphasized the communities and relationships they formed as keys to their humanity and right to freedom.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They were also keen to highlight their relationship to motherhood, so as to emphasize their shared traits with white women and the ways in which they too could meet traditional expectations of white women.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Harriet Jacobs's *Incidents in the Life of a Slave Girl* showcases her grandmother as the matriarch of her family, which shows how enslaved mothers are capable of nurturing like valued white women.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black women also played their role in the abolitionist movement, both domestically and internationally, showing involvement in US Foreign Relations.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] One notable example was Harriet Jacobs, who produced letters in England reflecting on her experiences as a slave in the US to challenge the pro-slavery movement in the USA.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The London Emancipation Committee published her letters into a book, titled: The Deeper Wrong: Incidents in the Life of a Slave Girl, Written by Herself.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The book was not just noticed in reform journals, but in the mainstream press.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Lengthy British reviews show how the book helped abolitionists win public support in Britain.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black abolitionist rhetoric could be done in literary form, a way for black women to have influence in an international abolitionist movement.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black abolitionist rhetoric was not only a transatlantic movement between Britain and the US, it also had influence in the Caribbean and South America.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The 1833 legal case Mundrucu v Barker also carried international importance in the abolitionist campaign.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In taking a stand against segregation, a black Brazilian immigrant had focused worldwide attention on racism in slaveholding US society.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Here there was division between white Philadelphians who saw black Saint Dominguan refugees as a threat to the city and country's racial order, their way of trying to justify slavery.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] This shows the connection between attitudes towards segregation and slavery helped shape black abolitionist rhetoric.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] This led to domestic organisations being established by interracial communities, such as the Boston Female Anti-Slavery Society.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Working as Jamaican-based writers for New York newspapers between 1840 and 1851, the two black US-Jamaican brothers, Henry and George Davison provided inter-American perspectives on abolitionism.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Henry wrote letters to the National Anti-Slavery Standard.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black Americans had opportunities to write for newspapers, providing publicity and discussion of abolitionist rhetoric.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Slavery was moving beyond internal US divisions, but reaching influence outside of the USA.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black abolitionist rhetoric was not simply an African-American activity, but involved South American and Caribbean individuals too, showing an international movement.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Angelina and Sarah Grimké were the first female anti-slavery agents, and played a variety of roles in the abolitionist movement.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Though born in the South, the Grimké sisters became disillusioned with slavery and moved North to get away from it.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Perhaps because of their birthplace, the Grimké sisters' critiques carried particular weight and specificity.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Angelina Grimké spoke of her thrill at seeing white men do manual labor of any kind.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Their perspectives as native Southerners as well as women, brought a new important point of view to the abolitionist movement.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1836, they moved to New York and began work for the Anti-Slavery Society, where they met and were impressed by William Lloyd Garrison.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The sisters wrote many pamphlets (Angelina's "Appeal to the Christian Women of the South" was the only appeal directly to Southern women to defy slavery laws) and played leadership roles at the first Anti-Slavery Convention of American Women in 1837.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Grimkés later made a notable speaking tour around the north, which culminated in Angelina's February 1838 address to a Committee of the Legislature of Massachusetts.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Lucretia Mott was also active in the abolitionist movement.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Though well known for her women's suffrage advocacy, Mott also played an important role in the abolitionist movement.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] During four decades, she delivered sermons about abolitionism, women's rights, and a host of other issues.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Mott acknowledged her Quaker beliefs' determinative role in affecting her abolitionist sentiment.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abby Kelley Foster, with a strong Quaker heritage, helped lead Susan B.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Anthony and Lucy Stone into the abolition movement, and encouraged them to take on a role in political activism.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] the first National Women's Rights Convention, held in Worcester, Massachusetts, in 1850.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (The better-known Seneca Falls Convention, held in 1848, was not national).
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] She was an "ultra" abolitionist who believed in immediate and complete civil rights for all slaves.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Since 1841, however, she had resigned from the Quakers over disputes about not allowing anti-slavery speakers in meeting houses (including the Uxbridge monthly meeting where she had attended with her family), and the group disowned her.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abby Kelley became a leading speaker and the leading fundraiser for the American Anti-slavery Society.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Radical abolitionism became known as "Abby Kelleyism".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Other leaders in the abolitionist movement were Lydia Maria Child, Elizabeth Cady Stanton, Susan B.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Anthony, Harriet Tubman, and Sojourner Truth.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] But even beyond these well-known women, abolitionism maintained impressive support from white middle-class and some black women.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] It was these women who performed many of the logistical, day-to-day tasks that made the movement successful.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They raised money, wrote and distributed propaganda pieces, drafted and signed petitions, and lobbied the legislatures.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Though abolitionism sowed the seeds of the women's rights movement, most women became involved in abolitionism because of a gendered religious worldview, and the idea that they had feminine, moral responsibilities.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] For example, in the winter of 1831–1832, women sent three petitions to the Virginia legislature, advocating emancipation of the state's slave population.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The only precedent for such action was Catharine Beecher's organization of a petition protesting the Cherokee removal.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Virginia petitions, while the first of their kind, were by no means the last.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Similar backing increased leading up to the Civil War.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Even as women played crucial roles in abolitionism, the movement simultaneously helped stimulate women's-rights efforts.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] A full 10 years before the Seneca Falls Convention, the Grimké sisters were travelling and lecturing about their experiences with slavery.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] As Gerda Lerner says, the Grimkés understood their actions' great impact.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] "In working for the liberation of the slave," Lerner writes, "Sarah and Angelina Grimké found the key to their own liberation.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] And the consciousness of the significance of their actions was clearly before them.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Women gained important experiences in public speaking and organizing that stood them in good stead going forward.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Grimké sisters' public speaking played a critical part in legitimizing women's place in the public sphere.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Some Christian women created cent societies to benefit abolition movements, where many women in a church would each pledge to donate one cent a week to help abolitionist causes.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Even though women were not allowed full access to political and religious spaces, they still played a big role in the abolitionist movement through both public activism and behind-the-scenes activism.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] As historian Julie Roy Jeffrey explains, a lot of women relied on their religious faith and authority to speak out against slavery and challenge male-led church systems that tried to keep them quiet.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They believed slavery went against Christian values and saw it as a deep moral wrong.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In their speeches and writing, they made it clear that true faith could not exist alongside a system that discriminated against people.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Women like Sarah Otis Ernst and Maria Child used persuasive writing, public speeches, and organizing work to fight not just slavery, but also the powerful systems that kept it going.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Ernst was a strong Garrisonian who got frustrated when mainstream abolitionists started watering down their message.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] She did not like that people in the movement were trying to be more politically strategic instead of sticking to the original beliefs, like full racial equality, immediate emancipation, and refusing to work with pro-slavery systems.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] At the 1852 American and Foreign Antislavery Society convention, around two-thirds of the 2,000 people there were women.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] That says a lot about how involved women were, even though they often got written out of the story.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They could not vote, but they used writing, speeches, and journalism to influence politics and public opinion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Their activism was real, public, and tied directly into national conversations.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] But not all women approached the movement the same way.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] There were clear differences between how white and Black women operated, and sometimes those differences caused conflict.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] White women, especially ones who were more religious, focused a lot on the moral and spiritual arguments.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They used Christian values to call out slavery as a sin and tried to appeal to other white Americans by framing it as a moral crisis.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] For example, Lydia Maria Child wrote about Christian duty and compassion to get people on board.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] But that type of activism did not always connect with what Black women were facing every day.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] And even inside the abolitionist circles, Black women were still often pushed to the side.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They were not always given speaking time, leadership roles, or space in published work.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Sojourner Truth had to fight just to speak at some events, and even then, people questioned her.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] White women could usually speak and be heard if they used moral language.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black women had to work twice as hard just to get into the room.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They faced racism from inside the movement and also from the outside world, which made it even harder for their voices to be heard.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Richmond talks about how central Black women were to abolition, even though they have been left out of most of the history.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] "Women like Sojourner Truth, Maria Stewart, and Harriet Tubman struggled not only for the abolition of slavery but for gender and racial equality as well".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They were not just giving speeches, they were founding antislavery groups, organizing communities, and building transatlantic networks.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They were working through both racism and sexism and still finding ways to be powerful voices.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Truth's line "Ain’t I a Woman?" and Stewart saying she had to "stand for justice wherever I find it" show how they were calling out not just slavery, but the whole system that tried to silence them.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Harriet Tubman took a different route; she led people to freedom through the Underground Railroad and even worked for the Union Army.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black women's abolitionism looked different from that of white women.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] It was rooted in their personal experience and often more direct and action-focused.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They made sure the fight for abolition was not just about ending slavery, but also about achieving full equality and justice.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The July 1848 Seneca Falls Convention grew out of a partnership between Lucretia Mott and Elizabeth Cady Stanton that blossomed while the two worked, at first, on abolitionist issues.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Indeed, the two met at the World's Anti-Slavery Convention in the summer of 1840.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Mott brought oratorical skills and an impressive reputation as an abolitionist to the nascent women's rights movement.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abolitionism brought together active women and enabled them to make political and personal connections while honing communication and organizational skills.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Even Sojourner Truth, commonly associated with abolitionism, delivered her first documented public speech at the 1850 National Women's Rights Convention in Worcester.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] There, she argued for women's reform activism.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The religious component of American abolitionism was great.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] It began with the Quakers, then moved to the other Protestants with the Second Great Awakening of the early 19th century.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Saying slavery was sinful made its evil easy to understand, and tended to arouse fervor for the cause.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The debate about slavery was often based on what the Bible said or did not say about it.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] John Brown, who had studied the Bible for the ministry, proclaimed that he was "an instrument of God".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Second Great Awakening of the 1820s and 1830s in religion inspired groups that undertook many types of social reform.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] For some that included the immediate abolition of slavery as they considered it sinful to hold slaves as well as to tolerate slavery.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Opposition to slavery, for example, was one of the works of piety of the Methodist Churches, which were established by John Wesley.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] "Abolitionist" had several meanings at the time.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The followers of William Lloyd Garrison, including Wendell Phillips and Frederick Douglass, demanded the "immediate abolition of slavery", hence the name, also called "immediatism".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] A more pragmatic group of abolitionists, such as Theodore Weld and Arthur Tappan, wanted immediate action, but were willing to support a program of gradual emancipation, with a long intermediate stage.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The *True Wesleyan* a periodical founded by Orange Scott and Jotham Horton was used to disseminate abolitionist views.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Methodist and Quaker branches of Christianity played an integral part in the formulation of abolitionist ideology in the United States.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] "Anti-slavery men", such as John Quincy Adams, did not call slavery a sin.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They called it an evil feature of society as a whole.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They did what they could to limit slavery and end it where possible, but were not part of any abolitionist group.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] For example, in 1841, John Quincy Adams represented the *Amistad* African slaves in the Supreme Court of the United States and argued that they should be set free.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In the last years before the war, "anti-slavery" could refer to the Northern majority, such as Abraham Lincoln, who opposed expansion of slavery or its influence, as by the Kansas–Nebraska Act or the Fugitive Slave Act.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Many Southerners called all these abolitionists, without distinguishing them from the Garrisonians.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Irish Catholics in the United States seldom challenged the role of slavery in society as it was protected at that time by the U.S.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They viewed the abolitionists as anti-Catholic and anti-Irish.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Irish Catholics were generally well received by Democrats in the South.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In contrast, most Irish Nationalists and Fenians supported the abolition of slavery.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Daniel O'Connell, the Catholic leader of the Irish in Ireland, supported abolition in the United States.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He organized a petition in Ireland with 60,000 signatures urging the Irish of the United States to support abolition.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] John O'Mahony, a founder of the Irish Republican Brotherhood was an abolitionist and served as colonel in the 69th Infantry Regiment during the Civil War.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Irish Catholics in the United States were recent immigrants; most were poor and very few owned slaves.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They had to compete with free blacks for unskilled labor jobs.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They saw abolitionism as the militant wing of evangelical anti-Catholic Protestantism.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Catholic Church in the United States had long ties in slaveholding Maryland and Louisiana.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1861, the Archbishop of New York wrote to Secretary of War Cameron: "That the Church is opposed to slavery ...
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Her doctrine on that subject is, that it is a crime to reduce men naturally free to a condition of servitude and bondage, as slaves." No American bishop supported extra-political abolition or interference with states' rights before the Civil War.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The secular Germans of the Forty-Eighter immigration were largely anti-slavery.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Prominent Forty-Eighters included Carl Schurz and Friedrich Hecker.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] German Lutherans seldom took a position on slavery, but German Methodists were anti-slavery.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Both Garrison's newspaper *The Liberator* and his book *Thoughts on African Colonization* (1832) arrived shortly after publication at Western Reserve College, in Hudson, Ohio, which was briefly the center of abolitionist discourse in the United States.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (John Brown grew up in Hudson.) The readers, including college president Charles Backus Storrs, found Garrison's arguments and evidence convincing.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abolition versus colonization rapidly became the primary issue on the campus, to the point that Storrs complained in writing that nothing else was being discussed.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The college's chaplain and theology professor Beriah Green said that "his *Thoughts* and his paper (*The Liberator*) are worthy of the eye and the heart of every American." Green delivered in the college chapel in November and December 1832 four sermons supporting immediate abolition of slavery.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] These so offended the college's trustees, more conservative than either the students or the faculty, that Green resigned, expecting that he would be fired.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Elizur Wright, another professor, resigned soon afterwards and became the first secretary of the American Anti-Slavery Society, of which Green was the first president.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Storrs contracted tuberculosis, took a leave of absence, and died within six months.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] This left the school with only one of its four professors.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Green was soon hired as the new president of the Oneida Institute.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Under the previous president, George Washington Gale, there had been a mass walkout of students; among the issues was Gale's lack of support for abolition.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He accepted the position on conditions that 1) he be allowed to preach "immediatism", immediate emancipation, and 2) that African-American students be admitted on the same terms as white students.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] These were accepted, and we know the names of 16 Blacks who studied there.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Native American students, of whom we know the names of two, were openly accepted as well.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Under Green, Oneida became "a hotbed of anti-slavery activity." It was "abolitionist to the core, more so than any other American college." For Presbyterian minister and Bible professor Green, slavery was not just an evil but a sin, and abolitionism was what Christ's principles mandated.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Under him a cadre of abolitionists was trained, who then carried the abolitionist message, via lectures and sermons, throughout the North.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Many future well-known black leaders and abolitionists were students at Oneida while Green was president.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] These include William Forten (son of James Forten), Alexander Crummell, Rev.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Oneida Institute did not have an incident, like that of Western Reserve, which brought national attention to it.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Its successor, Lane Seminary, in Cincinnati, did.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] "Lane was Oneida moved west." Leading the exodus from Oneida was a former Oneida student, and private student of Gale before that, Theodore Dwight Weld.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He greatly impressed the philanthropist brothers and abolitionists Arthur and Lewis Tappan.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They hired him to report on the movement nationally, and specifically to find a new location for their funding, since Oneida, a manual labor school, was a disappointment, according to Weld and his student followers.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] At the same time that Weld was scouting a location for a new school, the barely-functioning Lane Seminary was looking for students.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Based on Weld's recommendation, the Tappans started giving Lane the financial support they had previously given Oneida.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Weld, though on paper enrolled as a student at Lane, was de facto its head, choosing, through his recommendations to the Tappans, the president (Lyman Beecher, after Charles Grandison Finney, who became later the second president of Oberlin, turned it down), and telling the trustees whom to hire.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The group of students led by Weld constituted the first student movement in the history of the country.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He chose Lane, and they followed him there.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] When he soon left Lane for another new, struggling institution, Oberlin, they did so too, as a group.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Students, many of whom considered him the real leader of Lane, responded to Weld's announcement of the new school in Cincinnati.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Lane ended up with about 100 students, the most of any seminary in America.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] One of Weld's key contentions (and of Puritan abolition sentiment in general) was that slavery was inherently anti-family.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] While slave marriage was illegal, it happened frequently.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Slave owners expected their slaves to have many children to replace their numbers; Virginia and Maryland "exported" slaves to the Deep South—they were an asset like cattle—after Congress had banned the importation of slaves in 1808.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Since slaves were property they were frequently bought and sold, ripping apart families.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In his 1839 book *American Slavery as It Is*, Weld showed just how brutal the slave trade was towards families.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] To the very family-focused Puritans, this was one of the greatest crimes of slavery.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Weld's descriptions of families destroyed would later serve as the basis for scenes in *Uncle Tom's Cabin*, including Uncle Tom's being sold and separated from the children.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] No sooner had this disparate group of former Oneida students and others arrived at Lane, under the leadership of Weld, than they formed an anti-slavery society.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They then proceeded to hold a well-publicized series of debates on abolition versus African colonization, lasting 18 evenings, and decided that abolition was a much better solution to slavery.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In fact no real debate took place, since no one appeared to defend colonization.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] These "debates", which were well publicized, alarmed Lane's president Lyman Beecher and the school's trustees.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Adding to their alarm were the classes the students were holding in the Black community, teaching Blacks to read.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Fearing violence, since Cincinnati was strongly anti-abolitionist (see Cincinnati riots of 1829), they immediately prohibited any future such "off-the-topic" discussions and activities.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The students, again led by Weld, felt that abolitionism was so important – it was their responsibility as Christians to promote it – and they resigned *en masse*, joined by Asa Mahan, a trustee who supported the students.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] With support from the Tappans, they briefly tried to establish a new seminary, but as this did not prove a practical solution they accepted a proposal that they move as a group to the new Oberlin Collegiate Institute.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Due to its students' anti-slavery position, Oberlin soon became one of the most liberal colleges and accepted African-American students.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Along with Garrison, Northcutt and Collins were proponents of immediate abolition.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abby Kelley Foster became an "ultra abolitionist" and a follower of William Lloyd Garrison.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Anthony as well as Elizabeth Cady Stanton into the anti-slavery cause.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] After 1840, "abolition" usually referred to positions similar to Garrison's.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] It was largely an ideological movement led by about 3,000 people, including free blacks and free people of color, many of whom, such as Frederick Douglass in Rochester, New York, and Robert Purvis and James Forten in Philadelphia, played prominent leadership roles.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Douglass became legally free during a two-year stay in England, as British supporters raised funds to purchase his freedom from his American owner Thomas Auld, and also helped fund his abolitionist newspapers in the United States.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abolitionism had a strong religious base including Quakers, and people converted by the revivalist fervor of the Second Great Awakening, led by Charles Finney in the North, in the 1830s.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Belief in abolition contributed to the formation of Christian denominations, such as the Free Methodist Church.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Evangelical abolitionists founded some colleges, most notably Bates College in Maine and Oberlin College in Ohio.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The movement attracted such figures as Yale president Noah Porter and Harvard president Thomas Hill.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In the mid nineteenth century, American abolitionism was shaped by British ideological and organisational influences.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] A key part of this exchange was the intersection of abolitionism and free trade ideology.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] British reformers such as Richard Cobden and the Anti Corn Law League inspired American abolitionists to promote free trade arguing that it was morally and economically aligned to abolition in the United States.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Leaders like Joshua Leavitt, campaigner for the Liberty Party, argued that repealing British tariffs would reduce US reliance on Southern slave grown cotton and open markets to free labour goods from the North.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Another prominent British activist was George Thompson, who toured the US several times where he delivered speeches connecting Free Trade to the American abolition cause.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Figures like Cobden and Thompson were a direct influence on the ideology of Lloyd Garrison.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Another movement called the Free-produce movement extended across the Atlantic.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] This movement aimed to boycott goods produced by enslaved Africans.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The movement was connected to British activist Joseph Sturge and the idea that a free market allowed for consumer morality.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Sociologist Cecilia Walsh-Russo developed the term 'mutual brokerage' to refer to the interchange of ideas within UK-US abolitionist movements.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] She refers to the interactions which allowed ideas and political strategy to co-develop, rather than suggesting one learned from the other.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Walsh-Russo cites the 1840 World Anti-Slavery Convention in London as an example of mutual brokerage.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] She claims the exclusion of women as delegates, despite their presence at the events forced transatlantic abolitionist to re-assess their understanding of political participation and democracy, often leading to more progressive views in UK and US activism.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Despite exclusion from the conference women asserted their right to participate in the abolitionist cause by using informal setting such as salons to promote abolition.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] William Lloyd Garrison also engaged in Irish politics.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He communicated with key figures like Daniel O'Connell, which shaped his understanding of abolition as 'universal emancipation'.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Garrisonian abolitionists also used Ireland and the Irish as tools of comparison especially in combatting the American Colonization Society.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] However, efforts to forge direct relations between Irish Americans and African Americans largely failed.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The 1842 Address from the People of Ireland to Their Countrymen and Countrywomen in America, written by Irish abolitionists and signed by O'Connell, urged Irish Americans to support abolition and racial equality.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Garrisonians hoped this would foster diasporic responsibility among the Irish but it was rejected by most.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Irish immigrants, perhaps due to a desire to assimilate in the US, were overall not supportive of the abolitionist cause.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] It is easy to overstate the support for abolitionism in the North.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] A majority of white Southerners, though by no means all, supported slavery; there was a growing feeling in favor of emancipation in North Carolina, Maryland, Virginia, and Kentucky, until the panic resulting from Nat Turner's 1831 revolt put an end to it.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] But only a minority in the North supported abolition, seen as an extreme, "radical" measure.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (See Radical Republicans.) Horace Greeley remarked in 1854 that he had "never been able to discover any strong, pervading, over-ruling Anti Slavery sentiment in the Free States." Free blacks were subject in the North as well as in the South to conditions almost inconceivable today (2019).
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Although the picture is neither uniform nor static, in general free blacks in the North were not citizens and could neither vote nor hold public office.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They could not give testimony in court and their word was never taken against a white man's word, as a result of which white crimes against blacks were rarely punished.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black children could not study in the public schools, even though Black taxpayers helped support them, and there were only a handful of schools for Black students, like the African Free School in New York, the Abiel Smith School in Boston, and the Watkins Academy for Negro Youth in Baltimore.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] When schools for negroes were set up in Ohio in the 1830s, the teacher of one slept in it every night "for fear whites would burn it", and at another, "a vigilance committee threatened to tar and feather [the teacher] and ride her on a rail if she did not leave".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (Oberlin Collegiate Institute was the first college that survived to admit them by policy; the Oneida Institute was a short-lived predecessor.) In wages, housing, access to services, and transportation, separate but equal or Jim Crow treatment would have been a great improvement.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The proposal to create the country's first college for negros, in New Haven, Connecticut, got such strong local opposition (New Haven Excitement) that it was quickly abandoned.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Schools in which blacks and whites studied together in Canaan, New Hampshire, and Canterbury, Connecticut, were physically destroyed by mobs.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (The prosecutor was Francis Scott Key.) In Savannah, Georgia, the mayor and alderman protected an abolitionist visitor from a mob.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In the North there was far more serious violence by mobs, what the press sometimes called "mobocracy".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Lovejoy, who published an abolitionist newspaper, was killed by a mob in Illinois.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Only six months later, the large, modern, and expensive new hall which the Pennsylvania Anti-Slavery Society built in Philadelphia in 1838, was burned by a mob three days after it opened.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] There were other anti-abolitionist riots in New York (1834), Cincinnati (1829, 1836, and 1841), Norwich, Connecticut (1834), Washington, D.C.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (1835), Philadelphia (1842), and Granville, Ohio (following the Ohio State Anti-Slavery Convention, 1836), although there was also a pro-abolition riot (more precisely a pro-fugitive slave riot) in Boston in 1836 (and see Jerry Rescue).
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Between 1835 and 1838, anti-abolitionist violence "settled into a routine feature of public life in virtually all the major northern cities".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Giving to blacks the same rights that whites had, as Garrison called for, was "far outside the mainstream of opinion in the 1830s." Some opposed even allowing blacks to join abolitionist organizations.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abolitionists nationwide were outraged by the murder of white abolitionist and journalist Elijah Parish Lovejoy by a proslavery mob in Alton, Illinois on 7 November 1837.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Six months later, Pennsylvania Hall, an abolitionist venue in Philadelphia, was burnt to the ground by another proslavery mob on May 17, 1838.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Both events contributed to the growing American debate over slavery and marked an increase in violence against abolitionists in the United States.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Amos Dresser, a participant in the Lane Debates, was publicly whipped in Nashville.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] A gallows with a note from "Judge Lynch" was erected in front of Garrison's office.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He, along with the Tappans, was hung in effigy in Charleston, S.C.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Southern post offices burned rather than delivered abolitionist publications, in which they were supported by the national Post Office.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Slave owners were angry over the attacks on what some Southerners (including the politician John C.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Calhoun) referred to as their "peculiar institution" of slavery.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Starting in the 1830s, Southerners developed a vehement and growing ideological defense of slavery.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Slave owners claimed that slavery was not a necessary evil, or an evil of any sort; slavery was a positive good for masters and slaves alike, and it was explicitly sanctioned by God.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Biblical arguments were made in defense of slavery by religious leaders such as the Rev.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Ross and political leaders such as Jefferson Davis.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Southern Biblical interpretations contradicted those of the abolitionists; a popular one was that the curse on Noah's son Ham and his descendants in Africa justified enslaving blacks.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abolitionists responded, denying that either God or the Bible endorses slavery, at least as practiced in the Antebellum South.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In the early 19th century, a variety of organizations were established that advocated relocation of black people from the United States, most prominently the American Colonization Society (ACS), founded in 1816.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The ACS enjoyed the support of prominent Southern leaders such as Henry Clay and James Monroe, who saw it as a convenient means of relocating free blacks, whom they perceived as a threat to their control over enslaved blacks.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Starting in the 1820s, the ACS and affiliated state societies assisted a few thousand free blacks to move to the newly established colonies in West Africa that were to form the Republic of Liberia.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] From 1832 onward most of the migrants were enslaved people who had been freed on the condition that they go to Liberia.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Many migrants died of local diseases, but enough survived for Liberia to declare independence in 1847.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Americo-Liberians formed a ruling elite whose treatment of the native population followed the lines of disdain for African culture they had acquired in America.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Most African Americans opposed colonization, and simply wanted to be given the rights of free citizens in the United States.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] One notable opponent of such plans was the wealthy free black abolitionist James Forten of Philadelphia.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1832, prominent white abolitionist William Lloyd Garrison published his book *Thoughts on African Colonization*, in which he attacked severely the policy of sending blacks to (not "back to") Africa, and specifically the American Colonization Society.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Colonization Society, which he had previously supported, is "a creature without heart, without brains, eyeless, unnatural, hypocritical, relentless and unjust." "Colonization", according to Garrison, was not a plan to eliminate slavery, but to protect it.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Garrison also pointed out that a majority of the colonists died of disease, and the number of free blacks actually resettled in the future Liberia was minute in comparison to the number of slaves in the United States.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the United States, abortion is a divisive issue in politics and culture wars.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Prior to the mid-19th century, English common law formed the basis of abortion law in the colonies and the early Republic.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Connecticut was the first state to regulate abortion in 1821; it outlawed abortion after quickening, the moment in pregnancy when the pregnant woman starts to feel the fetus's movement in the uterus, and forbade the use of poisons to induce one post-quickening.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Many states subsequently passed various laws on abortion until the Supreme Court of the United States decisions of *Roe v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Bolton* decriminalized abortion nationwide in 1973.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The *Roe* decision imposed a federally mandated uniform framework for state legislation on the subject.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It also established a minimal period during which abortion is legal, with more or fewer restrictions throughout the pregnancy.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] That basic framework, modified in *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Casey* (1992), remained nominally in place, although the effective availability of abortion varied significantly from state to state, as many counties had no abortion providers.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2022, *Roe* and *Casey* were overturned in *Dobbs v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, ending protection of abortion rights by the United States Constitution and allowing individual states to regulate any aspect of abortion not preempted by federal law.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Since 1976, the Republican Party has generally sought to restrict abortion access based on the stage of pregnancy or to criminalize abortion, whereas the Democratic Party has generally defended access to abortion and has made contraception easier to obtain.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The abortion-rights movement advocates for patient choice and bodily autonomy, while the anti-abortion movement advocate that the fetus has a right to live.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Historically framed as a debate between the pro-choice and pro-life labels, most Americans agree with some positions of each side.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Support for abortion gradually increased in the U.S. beginning in the early 1970s, and stabilized during the 2010s.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The abortion rate has continuously declined from a peak in 1980 of 30 per 1,000 women of childbearing age (15–44) to 11.3 by 2018.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2018, 78% of abortions were performed at 9 weeks or less gestation, and 92% of abortions were performed at 13 weeks or less gestation.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By 2023, medication abortions accounted for 63% of all abortions.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Almost 25% of women will have had an abortion by age 45, with 20% of 30 year olds having had one.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2019, 60% of women who had abortions were already mothers, and 50% already had two or more children.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Increased access to birth control has been statistically linked to reductions in the abortion rate.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The first state to decriminalize abortion prior to *Roe* was Hawaii.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of 2025, Alaska, Arizona, California, Colorado, Illinois, Kansas, Maryland, Michigan, Minnesota, Missouri, Montana, New York, Ohio, Vermont, and Wyoming have a right to abortion in their state constitutions, either explicitly or as interpreted by the state supreme court.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Other states, such as Massachusetts and Oregon, protect abortion under state law.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The state constitutions of Alabama, Arkansas, Louisiana, Tennessee, and West Virginia explicitly contain no right to an abortion, while the state constitution of Nebraska prohibits abortion after the first trimester.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In medical parlance, "abortion" refers only to the end of an intrauterine pregnancy before the embryo or fetus can survive outside the uterus.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This is inclusive of spontaneous abortion (more commonly referred to as miscarriage or early pregnancy loss) and to induced abortion, where a pregnancy is ended through medication or a medical procedure.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The abortion debate most commonly relates to the induced abortion of a pregnancy, which is also how the term "abortion" is used in a legal sense.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Because abortion has been politicized, there has been a proliferation of ill-defined, inconsistently applied terms with no medical or clinical basis.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Concepts like "late-term abortion", or "partial-birth abortion" are not medical terms and do not have clinical significance.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Similarly, terms like "elective abortion" append unnecessary qualifiers that are not rooted in medical or legal distinctions.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists recommends using the terms "induced abortion" or simply "abortion" instead.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Additionally, some drugs that do not induce medical abortions, such as levonorgestrel, have been referred to as abortifacients by a US Senator.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Abortion in what eventually became the United States was governed by English Common law, which held that abortion after quickening was murder.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This was repeated by Henry de Bracton, Matthew Hale, and William Blackstone.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The common law on abortions before quickening was varying.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some historians argue that abortion was a fairly common practice in the history of the United States, and was not always controversial.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] At a time when society was more concerned with the more serious consequence of women becoming pregnant out of wedlock, family affairs were handled out of public view.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Abortion did not become a public controversy until the health risk of unsafe abortions by (female) unlicensed practitioners was brought to the public attention in the 19th century.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] James Mohr wrote that even though pre-quickening abortion was legal in the first three decades of the 19th century, only 1 in 25 to 1 in 30 pregnancies ended in abortion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By the 1850s and 1860s, this number had increased to 1 in 5 or 1 in 6.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] John Keown highlighted some challenges in pinning down the common law view, observing that "evidence of quickening would clearly facilitate prosecution".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the mid-18th century, Benjamin Franklin included a recipe for an abortifacient in a math textbook.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1728, Franklin condemned publisher Samuel Keimer for publishing an article on abortion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] According to biographer Walter Isaacson, Franklin did not have a strong view on the issue.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In *The Speech of Polly Baker*, Franklin places the blame for abortion and infanticide on the sexual double standard against women.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1716, New York passed an ordinance prohibiting midwives from providing abortion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Founding Father and Second President of the United States John Adams praised the Spartan lawgiver Lycurgus for refusing his sister-in-law from having an abortion even though it prevented him from assuming power.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Thomas Jefferson wrote approving of a quote by Montesquieu that "‘there is among savages another custom . . . it is the cruel practice of abortion." Jefferson added that the Natives stopped the practice after becoming "civilized".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Within the context of a sex scandal, Connecticut became the first state to regulate abortion by statute in 1821.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Many states subsequently passed various abortion laws.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1829, New York made post-quickening abortions a felony and pre-quickening abortions a misdemeanor.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This was followed by 10 of the 26 states creating similar restrictions within the next few decades, in particular by the 1860s and 1870s.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The first laws related to abortion were made to protect women from real or perceived risks, and those more restrictive penalized only the provider.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Criminalization did not end the practice of abortion; unlicensed doctors and midwives continued to perform them.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Most of the women receiving abortions from unlicensed practitioners were poor.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Women's safety continued to be a concern, especially after the highly publicized death of Mary Rogers.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wealthier women could pay willing physicians to broadly interpret health exceptions in their favor.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Euphemistic advertisements for abortifacients offered an assortment of herbal remedies.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A number of other factors likely played a role in the rise of anti-abortion laws.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As in Europe, abortion techniques advanced starting in the 17th century, and the conservatism of most in the medical profession with regards to sexual matters prevented the wide expansion of abortion techniques.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Physicians, who were the leading advocates of abortion criminalization laws, appear to have been motivated at least in part by advances in medical knowledge.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Science had discovered that fertilization inaugurated a more or less continuous process of development, which produced a new human being.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Quickening was found to be not more or less crucial in the process of gestation than any other step.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Many physicians concluded that if society considered it unjustifiable to terminate pregnancy after the fetus had quickened, and if quickening was a relatively unimportant step in the gestation process, then it was just as wrong to terminate a pregnancy before quickening as after quickening.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The doctors used flawed math to convince the American Medical Association to accept that pre-quickening abortion should also be outlawed, leading to the raft of state laws banning abortion in the latter half of the 19th century.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Doctors were also influenced by practical reasons to advocate anti-abortion laws.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] For one, abortion providers were usually female midwives without formal training or education.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In an age where the leading doctors in the nation were attempting to standardize the medical profession, these unlicensed practitioners were considered a nuisance to public health.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Despite campaigns to end the practice of abortion, abortifacient advertising was highly effective and abortion was commonly practiced, with the help of a midwife or other women, in the mid-19th century, although they were not always safe.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] While the precise abortion rate was not known, James Mohr's 1978 book *Abortion in America* documented multiple recorded estimates by 19th-century physicians, which suggested that between around 15% and 35% of all pregnancies ended in abortion during that period.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This era also saw a marked shift in the people who were obtaining abortions.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Before the start of the 19th century, most abortions were sought by unmarried women, who had become pregnant out of wedlock and for which there was much less compassion compared to married women who got an abortion; many of them were wealthy and paid well.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Out of 54 abortion cases published in American medical journals between 1839 and 1880, over half were sought by married women, and well over 60% of the married women already had at least one child.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The sense that married women were now frequently obtaining abortions worried many conservative physicians, who were almost exclusively men.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the Reconstruction era, much of the blame was placed on the burgeoning women's rights movement.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Although the medical profession expressed hostility toward feminism, many feminists of the era were also opposed to abortion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In *The Revolution*, a newspaper operated by Elizabeth Cady Stanton and Susan B.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Anthony, an 1869 opinion piece was published arguing that instead of merely attempting to pass a law against abortion, the root cause must also be addressed.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The writer stated that simply passing an anti-abortion law would be "only mowing off the top of the noxious weed, while the root remains. ...
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] No matter what the motive, love of ease, or a desire to save from suffering the unborn innocent, the woman is awfully guilty who commits the deed.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It will burden her conscience in life, it will burden her soul in death; But oh! thrice guilty is he who drove her to the desperation which impelled her to the crime." To many feminists of this era, abortion was regarded as an undesirable necessity forced upon women by thoughtless men.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The free love wing of the feminist movement refused to advocate for abortion and treated the practice as an example of the hideous extremes to which modern marriage was driving women.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Marital rape and the seduction of unmarried women were societal ills, which feminists believed caused the need to abort, as men did not respect women's right to abstinence.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Feminist opposition to abortion was much less prevalent by the 20th century, and it was feminists and physicians who came to question anti-abortion laws and raise public interest in the 1960s.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1873, Anthony Comstock created the New York Society for the Suppression of Vice, an institution dedicated to supervising the morality of the public.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Later that year, Comstock successfully influenced the United States Congress to pass the Comstock Law, which made it illegal to deliver through the U.S. mail any "obscene, lewd, or lascivious" material.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It also prohibited producing or publishing information pertaining to the procurement of abortion, birth control, and venereal disease, including to medical students.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The production, publication, importation, and distribution of such materials was suppressed under the Comstock Law as being obscene, and similar prohibitions were passed by 24 of the 37 states.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By 1900, abortion was normally a felony in every state.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some states included provisions allowing for abortion in limited circumstances, generally to protect the woman's health or to terminate pregnancies arising from rape or incest.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Most Americans did not view abortion as a crime, and abortions continued to occur and became increasingly available.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The American Birth Control League was founded by Margaret Sanger in 1921; it would become Planned Parenthood Federation of America in 1942.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By the 1930s, licensed physicians performed an estimated 800,000 abortions a year.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1988, 17 year old Becky Bell died from an infection after an unsafe abortion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] She lived in Indiana where parental consent was required to have a safe and legal abortion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Tribe wrote in *Abortion: The Clash of Absolutes* that Bell's best friend said that Becky considered an out-of-state abortion to get around Indiana's parental consent requirement.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It is possible she performed the abortion herself.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] However it was done, Becky died from an infection that was probably caused by the procedure.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Her parents publicly campaigned against parental consent laws after her death.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rosie Jimenez died from sepsis in 1977 following an abortion procedure at the home of a midwife who was not licensed to perform abortions.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] She did not go to a licensed physician because the Hyde Amendment barring public Medicaid funding for abortions had gone into effect after surviving a statutory challenge in *Beal v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Doe* and an Equal Protection challenge in *Maher v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Abu Hayat was convicted by a Manhattan Court in 1993 for performing an illegal third trimester abortion at his clinic in Alphabet City.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The doctor began the dilation and evacuation procedure which was not legal in the third trimester.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The baby was born alive before the procedure could be completed.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] She was missing an arm that had been severed during the D&E.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Hayat argued that he was protected from criminal conviction by *Roe v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* based on an argument that the baby had not yet been born when he attempted the procedure.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Another patient was forced to leave Hayat's clinic halfway through a procedure after Dr.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Hayat demanded more money that her husband could not afford to pay.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The patient nearly died and was treated at a local hospital for severe infection caused by pieces of dismembered fetus being left in her uterus.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] 17 year old Sophie McCoy died in 1990 from an infected uterine perforation after receiving an abortion at Dr.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Inequality in access to safe and legal abortions persists to this day whereby many women cannot afford to obtain a legal abortion; in such cases, women may turn to illegal abortion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the early 1960s, a controversy centered around children's television host Sherri Finkbine that helped bring abortion and abortion law more directly into the American public eye.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Living in the area of Phoenix, Arizona, Finkbine had had four healthy children; during her pregnancy with her fifth child, she discovered the child might have severe deformities when born.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This was likely because Finkbine had been taking sleeping pills that she was unaware contained thalidomide, a drug that increases the risk of fetal deformities during pregnancy.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Though Finkbine wanted an abortion, the abortion laws of Arizona only allowed abortions if a pregnancy posed a threat to the woman's life.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The situation gained public attention after Finkbine shared the story with a reporter from *The Arizona Republic*, who disclosed her identity in spite of her requests for anonymity.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On August 18, 1962, Finkbine traveled to Sweden to obtain a legal abortion, where it was confirmed that the fetus had severe deformities.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1964, Gerri Santoro of Connecticut died trying to obtain an illegal abortion, and her photo became the symbol of an abortion-rights movement.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some women's rights activist groups developed their own skills to provide abortions to women who could not obtain them elsewhere.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As an example, in Chicago, a group known as "Jane" operated a floating abortion clinic throughout much of the 1960s.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Women seeking the procedure would call a designated number and be given instructions on how to find "Jane".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Connecticut* struck down one of the remaining contraception Comstock laws in Connecticut and Massachusetts.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] However, *Griswold* only applied to marital relationships, allowing married couples to buy and use contraceptives without government restriction.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Baird*, to extend the precedent of *Griswold* to unmarried persons as well.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1967, Colorado became the first state to decriminalize abortion in cases of rape, incest, or in which pregnancy would lead to permanent physical disability of the woman.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Similar laws were passed in California, Oregon, and North Carolina.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1970, Hawaii became the first state to legalize abortions on the request of the woman, and New York repealed its 1830 law and allowed abortions up to the 24th week of pregnancy.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Similar laws were soon passed in Alaska and Washington.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1970, Washington held a referendum on legalizing early pregnancy abortions, becoming the first state to legalize abortion through a vote of the people.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A law in Washington, D.C., which allowed abortion to protect the life or health of the woman, was challenged in the Supreme Court in 1971 in *United States v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The court upheld the law, deeming that "health" meant "psychological and physical well-being", essentially allowing abortion in Washington, D.C.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By the end of 1972, 13 states had a law similar to that of Colorado, while Mississippi allowed abortion in cases of rape or incest only and Alabama and Massachusetts allowed abortions only in cases where the woman's physical health was endangered.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In order to obtain abortions during this period, women would often travel from a state where abortion was illegal to one where it was legal.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* was that abortion was illegal in 30 states and legal under certain circumstances in 20 states.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, 30 states prohibited abortion without exception, 16 states banned abortion except in certain special circumstances (e.g. rape, incest, and health threat to mother), 3 states allowed residents to obtain abortions, and New York allowed abortions generally.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Early that year, on January 22, 1973, the U.S.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* invalidated all of these laws, and set guidelines for the availability of abortion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The decision returned abortion to its liberalized pre-1820 status.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] *Roe* established that the right of privacy of a woman to obtain an abortion "must be considered against important state interests in regulation".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, the Court ruled that a Texas statute forbidding abortion except when necessary to save the life of the mother was unconstitutional.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court arrived at its decision by concluding that the issue of abortion and abortion rights falls under the right of privacy in the United States (e.g. federal constitutionally-protected right), in the sense of the right of a person not to be encroached by the state.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In its opinion, it listed several landmark cases where the court had previously found a right to privacy implied by the Constitution.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court did not recognize a right to abortion in all cases, saying: "State regulation protective of fetal life after viability thus has both logical and biological justifications.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court held that a right to privacy existed and included the right to have an abortion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The court found that a mother had a right to abortion until viability, a point to be determined by the abortion doctor.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] After viability a woman can obtain an abortion for health reasons, which the Court defined broadly to include psychological well-being.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A central issue in the *Roe* case and in the wider abortion debate in general is whether human life or personhood begins at conception, birth, or at some point in between.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court declined to make an attempt at resolving this issue, writing: "We need not resolve the difficult question of when life begins.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rather than asserting that human life begins at any specific point, the Court declared that the state has a "compelling interest" in protecting "potential life" at the point of viability.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, state governments may not prohibit late terminations of pregnancy when "necessary to preserve the life or health of the mother", even if it would cause the demise of a viable fetus.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This rule was clarified by the 1973 judicial decision *Doe v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Bolton*, which specifies "that the medical judgment may be exercised in the light of all factors—physical, emotional, psychological, familial, and the woman's age—relevant to the well-being of the patient".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It is by this provision for the mother's mental health that women in the U.S. legally choose abortion after viability when screenings reveal abnormalities that do not cause a baby to die shortly after birth.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the late 1960s, a number of organizations were formed to mobilize opinion both against and for the legalization of abortion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1966, the National Conference of Catholic Bishops assigned Monsignor James T.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] McHugh to document efforts to reform abortion laws, and anti-abortion groups began forming in various states in 1967.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1968, McHugh led an advisory group which became the National Right to Life Committee.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The forerunner of the NARAL Pro-Choice America was formed in 1969 to oppose restrictions on abortion and expand access to abortion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, in late 1973, NARAL became the National Abortion Rights Action League.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the 1992 case of *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Casey*, the Court abandoned *Roe's* strict trimester framework but maintained its central holding that women have a right to choose to have an abortion before viability.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] *Roe* had held that statutes regulating abortion must be subject to "strict scrutiny"—the traditional Supreme Court test for impositions upon fundamental Constitutional rights.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court continues to make decisions on this subject.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On April 18, 2007, it issued a ruling in the case of *Gonzales v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Carhart*, involving a federal law entitled the Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act of 2003 which President George W.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The law banned intact dilation and extraction, which opponents of abortion rights referred to as "partial-birth abortion", and stipulated that anyone breaking the law would get a prison sentence up to 2.5 years.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The United States Supreme Court upheld the 2003 ban by a narrow majority of 5–4, marking the first time the Court has allowed a ban on any type of abortion since 1973.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The opinion, which came from justice Anthony Kennedy, was joined by Justices Antonin Scalia, Clarence Thomas, and the two recent appointees, Samuel Alito and Chief Justice John Roberts.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Hellerstedt*, the Supreme Court in a 5–3 decision on June 27, 2016, swept away forms of state restrictions on the way abortion clinics can function.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court supported this argument and struck down these two provisions "facially" from the law at issue—that is, the very words of the provisions were invalid, no matter how they might be applied in any practical situation.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] According to the Supreme Court, the task of judging whether a law puts an unconstitutional burden on a woman's right to abortion belongs with the courts, and not the legislatures.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court ruled similarly in *June Medical Services, LLC v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Russo* on June 29, 2020, in a 5–4 decision that a Louisiana state law, modeled after the Texas law at the center of *Whole Woman's Health*, was unconstitutional.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Like Texas' law, the Louisiana law required certain measures for abortion clinics that, if having gone into effect, would have closed five of the six clinics in the state.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The case in Louisiana was put on hold pending the result of *Whole Woman's Health*, and was retried based on the Supreme Court's decision.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] While the District Court ruled the law unconstitutional, the Fifth Circuit found that unlike the Texas law, the burden of the Louisiana law passed the tests outlined in *Whole Woman's Health*, and thus the law was constitutional.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court issued an order to suspend enforcement of the law pending further review, and agreed to hear the case in full in October 2019.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It was the first abortion-related case to be heard by President Donald Trump's appointees to the Court, Neil Gorsuch and Brett Kavanaugh.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court found the Louisiana law unconstitutional for the same reasons as the Texas one, reversing the Fifth Circuit.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The judgment was supported by Chief Justice John Roberts who had dissented on *Whole Woman's Health* but joined in judgment as to upholding the court's respect for the past judgment in that case.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In December 2021, the FDA legalized telemedical provision of abortion pills with delivery by mail, after finding this to be safe and effective, and having suspended enforcement of previous restrictions during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of June that year, 31 states allowed the practice, fourteen required the prescribing clinician to be physically present, which effectively banned telemedicine, and five explicitly banned telemedical abortion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court granted *certiorari* to *Dobbs v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Jackson Women's Health Organization* in May 2021, a case that challenges the impact of *Roe v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* in blocking enforcement of a 2018 Mississippi law (the Gestational Age Act) that had banned any abortions after the first 15 weeks.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Oral arguments to *Dobbs* were held in December 2021, and a decision was expected by the end of the 2021–22 Supreme Court term.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On September 1, 2021, Texas passed the Texas Heartbeat Act, one of the most restrictive abortion laws in the nation, banning most procedures after six weeks.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On May 2, 2022, a leaked draft majority opinion for *Dobbs*, written by Samuel Alito, set to overturn *Roe* was reported by *Politico*.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On June 24, 2022, the Supreme Court overruled both *Roe* and *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Casey* in the *Dobbs* case on originalist grounds that a right to abortion cannot be found in the U.S.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] John Roberts, the Chief Justice of the United States, concurred in the decision to uphold the law at question as constitutional, by a 6–3 vote, but did not support overruling both *Roe* and *Casey*.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This enabled trigger laws, which had been passed in 13 states, to ban abortions in those states.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Voters in Ohio defeated August 2023 Ohio Issue 1, which intended to make changes to the state's constitution more difficult.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] November 2023 Ohio Issue 1 was then approved by a majority of voters, which added the right to an abortion to the Ohio constitution.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Although states nominally allow abortion to prevent the woman's imminent death, five women have died to pregnancy related issues in Texas alone due to doctors refusing to perform abortions because of the state's abortion law despite the *de jure* legal circumstances.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2026, 2024 Nevada Question 6 needs to be approved again to enshrine abortion in the state's constitution, while legislators in Hawaii, Virginia, and the state of Washington proposed similar amendments to codify abortion rights in 2026.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Gerardo Flores was convicted of two counts of capital murder in 2005 under Texas' fetal homicide law.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] His girlfriend Erica Basoria testified that she had asked him to step on her stomach because her attempts to induce miscarriage on herself had been unsuccessful.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Flores said he initially refused but she would not relent until he agreed.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Flores admitted to police that he "accidentally, probably" hit Basoria in the face during a fight on the night of the miscarriage.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Basoria told police that he was not abusive.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Texas' fetal homicide law did not allow charges against the mother because she had a right to terminate pregnancy, so only Flores was charged.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2019 a woman in Alabama was indicted after she was shot in the stomach for intentionally causing the death of "unborn baby Jones by initiating a fight knowing she was five months pregnant".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Medical abortion via mifepristone and misoprostol was approved for abortion in the United States by the FDA in September 2000.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of 2007, it was legal and available in all 50 states, Washington, D.C., Guam, and Puerto Rico.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It is a prescription drug, but was not initially available to the public through pharmacies; its distribution is primarily restricted to specially qualified licensed physicians, sold by Danco Laboratories under the brand name Mifeprex.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] French pharmaceutical company Roussel-Uclaf, (the company that synthesized mifepristone in 1980 and took it through clinical trials for approval in France by 1988) did not seek US approval, so in the United States legal availability was not initially possible.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The United States banned importation of mifepristone for personal use in 1989, a decision supported by Roussel Uclaf.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1994, Roussel Uclaf gave the U.S. drug rights to the Population Council in exchange for immunity from any product liability claims.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Population Council sponsored clinical trials in the United States.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The drug went on approvable status from 1996.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Production was intended to begin through the Danco Group in 1996, but they withdrew briefly in 1997 due to a corrupt business partner, delaying availability again.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Mifepristone was approved for abortion in the United States by the FDA in September 2000.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2016, the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) approved mifepristone, to end a pregnancy through 70 days gestation (70 days or less since the first day of a woman's last menstrual period).
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The approved dosing regimen is 200 mg of mifepristone taken by mouth (swallowed).
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] 24 to 48 hours after taking mifepristone, 800 mcg (micrograms) of misoprostol is taken buccally (in the cheek pouch), at a location appropriate for the patient.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of September 2021, in 32 states, the drug could only be provided by a licensed physician, and in 19 states, the prescribing clinician was required to be physically in the room with the patient while they are taking the drug.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the midst of the COVID-19 pandemic on December 16, 2021, in light of the difficulties in accessing in-person healthcare services, the FDA approved the distribution of mifepristone via mail.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On 16 December 2021, the FDA voluntarily adopted a new rule permanently relaxing the requirement that the pill be obtained in person, allowing it to be sent through the mail.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A prescription is still required, so that a doctor can screen for risk factors that would make taking the pill unsafe for the mother.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In January 2023, the FDA further relaxed rules, allowing any retail pharmacy to become certified to fill mifepristone prescriptions.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Department of Justice stated that USPS mailing of pills for medication abortion, even into states where abortion services are restricted, does not violate federal law.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2023, online access to abortion medication by mail delivered by the U.S.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Postal Service is currently available to citizens of all states.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In light of the *Dobbs* decision, the Alliance Defending Freedom launched a lawsuit in November 2022 in the Northern District of Texas under Judge Matthew J.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Kacsmaryk to seek to overturn the FDA's original approval of mifepristone.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Judge Kacsmaryk ruled for the Alliance on April 7, 2023, reversing the FDA's approval and banning mifepristone across the United States after seven days.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A district judge in a separate lawsuit, Thomas O.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rice of the Eastern District of Washington, ruled that the FDA should not reverse access to mifepristone in 16 states.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Kacsmaryk's ruling was partially reversed by a panel on the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, leaving mifepristone on the market but reverting efforts made by the FDA to liberalize its use over seven years.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The case was appealed to the Supreme Court, and on June 13, 2024, the court ruled that the Alliance Defending Freedom lacked standing to bring the suit.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In January 2023, GenBioPro filed suit to overturn state laws that prohibit sale of mifepristone, claiming that such laws are invalid because it is a federally approved drug.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The argument that state laws seeking to ban or restrict the use of mifepristone are preempted by the FDA's decision to make the drug available is supported by a number of Supreme Court decisions, including opinions by the traditionally more conservative Justices.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In March 2023, Wyoming became the first US state to ban the pill.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In April 2023, in a lawsuit brought by 17 US states and the District of Columbia, federal district judge Thomas O.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rice issued a temporary injunction that the FDA should not reduce access to mifepristone in these states and the district.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In May 2024, the state of Louisiana classified mifepristone and misoprostol as controlled substances, with penalties for possession without a prescription.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The move follows concerns over coerced abortion and has drawn criticism from over 240 doctors in the state.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In December 2025, the states of Florida and Texas filed a lawsuit against the FDA challenging its approval of mifepristone in 2000 and approval of a generic in 2025.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] After regulations on abortion early in pregnancy were ruled constitutional by the 2022 decision *Dobbs v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, some states enacted restrictions on abortions and abortion pills.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In January 2023, the United States Department of Justice issued an interpretation of the Comstock Act that it was legal for United States Postal Service employees to deliver the pills in any state, because they could not know whether the pills would be used for an abortion or other purposes.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Alliance for Hippocratic Medicine* lawsuit, federal district judge Matthew J.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Kacsmaryk issued a preliminary injunction suspending the 2000 approval of mifepristone, which would take effect a week later.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Fifth Circuit reversed parts of Kacsmaryk's injunction, but placed a temporary injunction on the 2016 REMS change to mifepristone.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On appeal to the Supreme Court, the Court stayed both injunctions on 21 April 2023, with only Justices Samuel Alito and Clarence Thomas stating their dissent.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The stay allowed mifepristone to remain legally available while the lower courts consider the merits of the case.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In June 2024, the US Supreme Court unanimously overturned judge Kacsmaryk's Fifth Circuit decision on the grounds that the Alliance for Hippocratic Medicine had no standing to challenge the FDA's regulations of mifepristone.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court ruled that Alliance for Hippocratic Medicine did not demonstrate that they would suffer harm to warrant standing.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court did not rule on the substance of mifepristone, abortion, or the FDA's procedures.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some drugs are approved by the FDA under subsection H, which has two subparts.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The first sets forth ways to rush experimental drugs, such as aggressive HIV and cancer treatments, to market when speedy approval is deemed vital to the health of potential patients.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The second part of subsection H applies to drugs that not only must meet restrictions for use due to safety requirements, but also are required to meet postmarketing surveillance to establish that the safety results shown in clinical trials are seconded by use in a much wider population.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Until December 2021, Mifepristone was approved under the second part of subsection H.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The result is that women could not pick the drug up at a pharmacy, but were required to receive it directly from a doctor.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The approval of mifepristone under subsection H included a black box warning.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] During the COVID pandemic, and coupled with growing restrictions on abortion access in conservative states, the FDA performed trial runs of telemedical abortions, allowing doctors to prescribe mifepristone and other medical abortion drugs without an in-person visit by the patient.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By December 2021, the FDA advanced approval to for telemedical abortions for all registered providers. which was made final by 2023.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of July 2025, 25 states allowed telemedical abortions, the prescription of medical abortion drugs without an in-person visit to a doctor, without restriction, 13 states allowed abortion but had restrictions on telemedical abortions, and 12 states banned abortion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The FDA's action, coupled with the *Dobbs* decision, led many conservative states to seek new laws to ban citizens in their states from telemedical abortion, or seeking penalties from those that prescribe that medication from other states.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As a result, eight states where telemedical abortion was legal passed shield laws shield laws to enable physicians to remotely prescribe abortion medication to patients in states where abortion is banned.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In October 2025, Louisiana Attorney General Liz Murrill and the Alliance Defending Freedom filed Louisiana v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] FDA against the Food and Drug Administration and Department of Health and Human Services challenging the 2023 Risk Evaluation and Mitigation Strategies (REMS) for mifepristone which removed the in-person dispensing requirement.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Republican Attorneys General of 21 states filed in support of Louisiana's lawsuit.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The lawsuit is one of several brought by Republican Attorneys General seeking to restrict mifepristone.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Joseph paused the case while the second Trump administration conducts a review of the 2023 REMS.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On May 1, 2026, Republican-appointed Judges Kyle Duncan, Leslie H.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Engelhardt on the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals unanimously blocked the 2023 REMS, preventing the mailing of mifepristone country-wide.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] However, the Supreme Court temporarily lifted the Fifth Circuit's order via the shadow docket on May 4, and stayed it for an indefinite period on May 14, over dissent from Alito and Thomas.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The ruling will remain in effect through at least the course of the Louisiana-FDA lawsuit, which is expected to continue into the year 2027.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Beyond limitations pertaining to abortion in the context of federal funding, there is little federal legislation protecting or penalizing abortion in the United States.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act of 2003, Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act of 1994, and Comstock Act of 1873 are some of the few pieces of existing federal law that provide substantive criminal provisions either protecting or penalizing abortion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The provisions in the Partial Birth Abortion Ban Act and the Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act cover activity affecting interstate or foreign commerce, to which the former was upheld (against constitutional attack under the 5th amendment) by the Supreme Court in *Gonzales v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The provisions of the Comstock Act primarily cover activity using the mail or postal system, and the Comstock Act was first upheld by Supreme Court in *Ex parte Jackson* (1878).
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The legality of abortion is frequently a major issue in nomination battles for the U.S.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Nominees typically remain silent on the issue during their hearings, as the issue may come before them as judges.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2021, the Women's Health Protection Act, which would protect abortion rights by federal statute, was introduced by Judy Chu.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] House of Representatives but was rejected by the U.S.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] After the *Dobbs* decision, Merrick Garland, then-U.S.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Attorney General, asserted that under federal law, states do not have the power to restrict access to FDA-approved abortion pills.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Currently, 13 states have criminal penalties for performing abortions, regardless of gestational age.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The penalties in states that have made abortion illegal vary, as outlined below.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] This chart lists only the penalties authorized specifically by the state laws which explicitly restrict (or ban) abortions.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The chart does not address the risk of being prosecuted for violating any other law because of the abortion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] States with criminal penalties that are blocked by a court or have yet to take effect are denoted by a gray background.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Prior to 2021, abortion was legal in all U.S. states, and every state had at least one abortion clinic.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion is a controversial political issue, and regular attempts to restrict it occur in most states.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Two such cases, originating in Texas and Louisiana, led to the Supreme Court cases of *Whole Woman's Health v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Hellerstedt* (2016) and *June Medical Services, LLC v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Russo* (2020) in which several Texas and Louisiana restrictions were struck down.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The issue of minors and abortion is regulated at the state level, and 37 states require some parental involvement, either in the form of parental consent or in the form of parental notification.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In certain situations, the parental restrictions can be overridden by a court.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Mandatory waiting periods, mandatory ultrasounds and scripted counseling are common abortion regulations.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion laws are generally stricter in conservative Southern states than they are in other parts of the country.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2019, New York passed the Reproductive Health Act (RHA), which repealed a pre-*Roe* provision that banned third-trimester abortions except in cases where the continuation of the pregnancy endangered a pregnant woman's life.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion in the Northern Mariana Islands, a United States Commonwealth territory, is illegal.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Alabama House Republicans passed a law on April 30, 2019, that will criminalize most abortion if it goes into effect.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Dubbed the "Human Life Protection Act", it offers only two exceptions: serious health risk to the mother or a lethal fetal anomaly.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Amendments that would have added cases of rape or incest to the list of exceptions were rejected It will also make the procedure a Class A felony.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Twenty-five male Alabama senators voted to pass the law on May 13.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The next day, Alabama governor Kay Ivey signed the bill into law, primarily as a symbolic gesture in hopes of challenging *Roe v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Since Alabama introduced the first modern anti-abortion legislation in April 2019, five other states have also adopted abortion laws including Mississippi, Kentucky, Ohio, Georgia and most recently Louisiana on May 30, 2019.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Supreme Court upheld an Indiana state law that requires fetuses which were aborted be buried or cremated.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In a December 2019 case, the court declined to review a lower court decision which upheld a Kentucky law requiring doctors to perform ultrasounds and show fetal images to patients before abortions.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] On June 29, 2020, previous Supreme Court rulings banning abortion restrictions appeared to be upheld when the U.S.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Supreme Court struck down the Louisiana anti-abortion law.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Following the ruling, the legality of laws restricting abortion in states such as Ohio was then called into question.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] It was also noted that Supreme Court Chief Justice John Roberts, who agreed that the Louisiana anti-abortion law was unconstitutional, had previously voted to uphold a similar law in Texas which was struck down by the U.S.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In order to avoid traditional constitutional challenges based on *Roe v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Plaintiffs sought an order from the U.S.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Supreme Court to stop the law from coming into effect, but the Court issued a denial of the order late on September 1, 2021, allowing the law to remain in effect.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] While unsigned, Chief Justice John Roberts and Justice Stephen Breyer wrote dissenting opinions joined by Justices Elena Kagan and Sonia Sotomayor that they would have granted an injunction on the law until a proper judicial review.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Garland further noted that the United States government has "an obligation to ensure that no state can deprive individuals of their constitutional rights." The Complaint avers that Texas enacted the law "in open defiance of the Constitution".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] District Court in Austin, Texas includes a declaration that the Texas Act is unconstitutional, and an injunction against state actors as well as any and all private individuals who may bring a SB 8 action.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The idea of asking a federal court to impose an injunction upon the entire civilian population of a state is unprecedented and has drawn eyebrows.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In April 2022 Colorado passed into law its Reproductive Health Equity Act, which assures abortion rights for all citizens of the state.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] On May 25, 2022, Oklahoma imposed a ban on almost all abortions after Oklahoma Governor Kevin Stitt signed House Bill 4327.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The bill bans abortion beginning at conception, with exceptions only in cases of "rape, sexual assault, or incest that has been reported to law enforcement", or if "the abortion is necessary to save the life of a pregnant woman in a medical emergency".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The law also permits private citizens to file lawsuits against (1) abortion providers (2) any individual who "aids and abets" an induced abortion, including paying for an abortion through insurance or otherwise, or (3) any individuals who *intend* to provide or to aid and abet an induced abortion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A lawsuit was immediately filed by the ACLU in opposition to the bill.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] At the time of enactment, Oklahoma was the only U.S. state to have passed a bill imposing such restrictions; the law made Oklahoma the first U.S. state to ban induced abortion procedures since prior to the ruling and implementation of *Roe* in 1973.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] on June 24, 2022, after the Supreme Court overturned *Roe*, Texas and Missouri immediately banned abortions with the exception only if the pregnancy was deemed to be particularly life-threatening.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] On January 28, 2023, the Minnesota state Senate passed a bill guaranteeing women's rights to abortion and other reproductive medicine which was signed into law on January 31.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The bill prohibits state and local governments from attempting to restrict access to sterilization or prenatal care, while also requiring contraceptive cost compensation.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In June 2024 abortion in Iowa was made illegal after 6 weeks of gestation, with exceptions for rape, incest, foetal abnormalities, and the mother's life.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2023, five women launched a class action lawsuit against the State of Texas after they were reportedly denied abortions at a clinic in the State despite grave risks to their life.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Four of the women traveled out of state in order to obtain an abortion, while the fifth only received the abortion in Texas when she was hospitalized after the fetus suffered a premature rupture of membranes.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The case argues that the Texas law, which allows abortion if there is a health risk to the mother, is too vague and doctors will not perform an abortion for fear of legal repercussions.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Amid the COVID-19 pandemic, anti-abortion government officials in several American states enacted or attempted to enact restrictions on abortion, characterizing it as a non-essential procedure that can be suspended during the medical emergency.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The orders have led to several legal challenges and criticism by human rights groups and several national medical organizations, including the American Medical Association.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Legal challenges on behalf of abortion providers, many of which were represented by the American Civil Liberties Union and Planned Parenthood, successfully stopped most of the orders on a temporary basis.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] One challenge was made against the FDA's rule on the distribution of mifepristone (RU-486), one of the two-part drug regimen to induce abortions.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Since 2000, it is only available through health providers under the FDA's ruling.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, access to mifepristone was a concern, and the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists along with other groups sued to have the rule relaxed to allow women to be able to access mifepristone at home through mail-order or retail pharmacies.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] While the Fourth Circuit issued a preliminary injunction against the FDA's ruling that would have allowed wider distribution, the Supreme Court ordered in a 6–3 decision in January 2021 to put a stay on the injunction, maintaining the FDA's rule.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Since 2019, the anti-abortion movement in the United States has sought declarations of "sanctuary cit[ies] for the unborn".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In June 2019, the city council of Waskom, Texas, voted to outlaw abortion in the city, declaring Waskom a "sanctuary city for the unborn" (the first such city to designate itself as such), as state governments elsewhere in the United States were also drafting abortion bans.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] As of July 2019, there is no abortion clinic in the city.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The Waskom ordinance has led other small cities in Texas, and as of April 2021 in Nebraska, to vote in favor of becoming "sanctuary cities for the unborn".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] On April 6, 2021, Hayes Center, Nebraska, became the first city in Nebraska to outlaw abortion by local ordinance, declaring itself a "sanctuary city for the unborn." The city of Blue Hill, Nebraska, followed suit and enacted a similar ordinance outlawing abortion on April 13, 2021.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In May 2021, Lubbock, Texas, with a population of less than 270,000, voted to ban abortion with the "sanctuary city for the unborn ordinance", becoming the largest city in the U.S. to ban abortion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion rights movements have also pushed for similar counterpart legislation in other cities.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The abortion debate has also been extended to the question of who pays the medical costs of the procedure, with some states using the mechanism as a way of reducing the number of abortions.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The cost of an abortion varies depending on factors such as location, facility, timing, type of procedure, and whether or not there is insurance or some other type of financial assistance.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2022, a medication abortion cost was about $580 at Planned Parenthood, though it could be more, up to around $800, in other facilities.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] During the first trimester an in-clinic abortion cost up to around $800, though often less; the average cost at Planned Parenthood was about $600.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A second trimester procedure varied depending on the stage of pregnancy.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The average ranged from about $715 earlier in the second trimester to $1,500–2,000 later in the second trimester.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A variety of resources from support organizations are available to contribute to the costs of the procedure, as well as travel expenses.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A variety of organizations offer financial support for people seeking abortions, including travel and other expenses.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Access Reproductive Care–Southeast (ARC Southeast), the Brigid Alliance, the Midwest Access Coalition (MAC), and the National Network of Abortion Funds are examples of such groups.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The Hyde Amendment is a federal legislative provision barring the use of federal Medicaid funds to pay for abortions except for rape and incest.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The provision, in various forms, was in response to *Roe v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Wade*, and has been routinely attached to annual appropriations bills since 1976, and represented the first major legislative success by the pro-life movement.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The law requires that states cover abortions under Medicaid in the event of rape, incest, and life endangerment.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Under this policy, U.S. federal funding to NGOs that provide abortion is not permitted.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The policy was first announced by President Ronald Reagan in 1984.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] It has been rescinded by Democratic presidents and reinstated by Republican presidents.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The policy was rescinded in 2021 by President Joe Biden and reinstated on January 24, 2025, by President Donald Trump.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Qualifying requirements for performing abortions vary from state to state.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Vermont has allowed physician assistants to do some first-trimester abortions since the mid-1970s.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] More recently, several states have changed their requirements for abortion providers, anticipating that the Supreme Court would overturn *Roe v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Wade*; now that the court has done so, more states are expanding eligibility to provide abortions.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In other states, non-physicians are not permitted to perform abortions.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Because reporting of abortions is not mandatory, statistics are of varying reliability.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Both the Centers For Disease Control (CDC) and the Guttmacher Institute regularly compile these statistics.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] However, in 2024 the Guttmacher Institute raised alarm that the Trump administration has severely gutted CDC efforts to collect these data.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The annual number of legal induced abortions in the U.S. doubled between 1973 and 1979, and peaked in 1990.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] There was a slow but steady decline throughout the 1990s.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Overall, the number of annual abortions decreased by 6% between 2000 and 2009, with temporary spikes in 2002 and 2006.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] By 2011, abortion rate in the nation dropped to its lowest point since the Supreme Court legalized the procedure.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] According to a study performed by Guttmacher Institute, long-acting contraceptive methods had a significant impact in reducing unwanted pregnancies.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] There were fewer than 17 abortions for every 1,000 women of child-bearing age.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] That was a 13%-decrease from 2008's numbers and slightly higher than the rate in 1973, when the Supreme Court's *Roe v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The study indicated a long-term decline in the abortion rate.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2016, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) reported 623,471 abortions, a 2% decrease from 636,902 in 2015.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] During the first six months of 2023 (following *Dobbs* in 2022), the numbers of abortions in certain U.S. states changed dramatically compared to the same time period in 2020, according to the Guttmacher Institute.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortions tripled in New Mexico and Wyoming and more than doubled in South Carolina and Kansas.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] For 13 states that had banned abortion, the Guttmacher Institute had no 2023 data to make the comparison.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A Guttmacher Institute survey of abortion providers estimated that early medical abortions accounted for 17% of all non-hospital abortions and slightly over one-quarter of abortions before 9 weeks gestation in the United States in 2008.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Medical abortions accounted for 32% of first-trimester abortions at Planned Parenthood clinics in 2008.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] By 2020, medication abortions accounted for more than 50% of all abortions.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2023, medication abortions obtained within the formal health care system had risen to 63% of all abortions, with the total percentage (which would include self-managed abortions by individuals in states with total bans) likely higher.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A majority of abortions are obtained by religiously identified women.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] According to the Guttmacher Institute, "more than 7 in 10 U.S. women obtaining an abortion report a religious affiliation (37% Protestant, 28% Catholic, and 7% other), and 25% attend religious services at least once a month.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion rates tend to be higher among minority women in the United States.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2000–2001, the rates among black and Hispanic women were 49 per 1,000 and 33 per 1,000, respectively, vs.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] 13 per 1,000 among non-Hispanic white women.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] This figure includes all women of reproductive age, including women that are not pregnant.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In other words, these abortion rates reflect the rate at which U.S. women of reproductive age have an abortion each year.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2004, the rates of abortion by ethnicity in the U.S. were 50 abortions per 1,000 black women, 28 abortions per 1,000 Hispanic women, and 11 abortions per 1,000 white women.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Wade legalized abortion nationwide in 1973.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1972, 41% of abortions were performed on women outside their state of residence, while in 1973 it declined to 21%, and then to 11% in 1974.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In the decade from 2011 to 2020, during which many states increased abortion restrictions, the percentage of women nationwide who traveled out of state for an abortion increased steadily, from 6% in 2011 to 9% in 2020.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Out of state travel for an abortion was much more prevalent in the 29 states hostile to abortion rights, with percentages in those states rising from 9% in 2011 to 15% by 2020, while in states supportive of abortion rights, out of state travel for abortions rose from 2% to 3% between 2011 and 2020.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2024, around 155,000 people crossed state lines for abortions, doubling the number in 2020.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In several states the percentage of abortions performed within the state specifically for people who traveled from outside of the state exceeds 15%, with Kansas, New Mexico, and Washington DC exceeding 50%.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Illinois performed the most out-of-state abortions in the US at 23% or 34,900 cases.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In contrast, from 2017 to 2020, the *abortion rate by state of residence* for Missourians went up by 18% from 8.4 to 9.9.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Some out of state travel pertains to locations of population centers in states; if large cities are close to state borders it may be common to cross borders for an abortion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] For example, Delaware, which is generally supportive of abortion rights, saw 44% of residents obtain their abortions in neighboring states.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The source of this information takes findings into account from 27 nations including the United States, and therefore, these findings may not be typical for any one nation.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2000, cases of rape or incest accounted for 1% of abortions.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A 2008 National Survey of Family Growth (NSFG) shows that rates of unintended pregnancy are highest among Blacks, Hispanics, and women with lower socio-economic status.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] According to the Centers for Disease Control, in 2011, most (64.5%) abortions were performed by ≤8 weeks' gestation, and nearly all (91.4%) were performed by ≤13 weeks' gestation.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Few abortions (7.3%) were performed between 14 and 20 weeks' gestation or at ≥21 weeks' gestation (1.4%).
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] From 2002 to 2011, the percentage of all abortions performed at ≤8 weeks' gestation increased 6%.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The risk of death from carrying a child to term in the U.S. is approximately 14 times greater than the risk of death from a legal abortion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2012, the mortality rate from legal abortion was 0.6 abortion-related deaths per 100,000 abortions.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The risk of abortion-related mortality increases with gestational age, but remains lower than that of childbirth through at least 21 weeks' gestation.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] For the period 2013 – 2019, the rate of mortality from legal abortion procedures in the US was 0.43 abortion-related deaths per 100,000 reported legal abortions, lower than the rates for previous 5-year periods.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2019, there were four identified deaths related to abortion in the US, out of 625,000 abortions.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] As an element of family planning, birth control was federally subsidized for low income families in 1965 under President Lyndon B.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1970, Congress passed Title X to provide family planning services for those in need, and President Richard Nixon signed it into law.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Funding for Title X rose from $6 million in 1971 to $61 million the next year, and slowly increased each year to $317 million in 2010, after which it was reduced by a few percent.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2011, the Guttmacher Institute reported that the number of abortions in the U.S. would be nearly two-thirds higher without access to birth control.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2015, the Federation of American Scientists reported that federally mandated access to birth control had helped reduce teenage pregnancies in the U.S. by 44 percent, and had prevented more than 188,000 unintended pregnancies.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The level of support for access to abortion has been relatively consistent since 1972.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Large majorities (over 75%) support access to abortion in "traumatic" cases (rape, danger to the mother's health, or strong chance of birth defects) and approximately 40-50% support elective abortion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Americans have been equally divided on the issue; a May 2018 Gallup poll indicated that 48% of Americans described themselves as "pro-choice" and 48% described themselves as "pro-life".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A July 2018 poll indicated that 64% of Americans did not want the Supreme Court to overturn *Roe v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The same poll found that support for abortion being generally legal was 60% during the first trimester of pregnancy, dropping to 28% in the second trimester, and 13% in the third trimester.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In January 2013, a majority of Americans believed abortion should be legal in all or most cases, according to a poll by NBC News and *The Wall Street Journal*.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Approximately 70% of respondents in the same poll opposed *Roe v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A poll by the Pew Research Center yielded similar results.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Moreover, 48% of Republicans opposed overturning *Roe*, compared to 46% who supported overturning it.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Gallup declared in May 2010 that more Americans identifying as "pro-life" is "the new normal", while also noting that there had been no increase in opposition to abortion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] It suggested that political polarization may have prompted more Republicans to call themselves "pro-life".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The terms "pro-choice" and "pro-life" do not always reflect a political view or fall along a binary; in one Public Religion Research Institute poll, seven in ten Americans described themselves as "pro-choice" while almost two-thirds described themselves as "pro-life".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The same poll found that 56% of Americans were in favor of legal access to abortion in all or some cases.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] 90% approve of abortion when the health of the woman is endangered, 77.4% when there is a strong chance of defects in the baby that could result from the pregnancy, and 79.5% when the pregnancy is the result of rape.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A 2022 poll by the Pew Research Center, found that 47% polled said that women who had an illegal abortion should face a penalty.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] 14% said they should face jail time, 16% said a fine or community services and 17% were not sure the penalty.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Wade and significantly reduced access to abortion, dissatisfaction with the country's abortion policies rose to 69% (the highest level in 23 years), of which 46% want fewer restrictions on abortion, a significant increase from previous years.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Since then, a consistent majority of the public has identified as pro-choice, with 52% identifying as pro-choice and 44% as pro-life in May 2023.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Pew Research Center polling shows little change in views from 2008 to 2012; modest differences based on gender or age.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The original article's table also shows by party affiliation, religion, and education level.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Support for the legalization of abortion is significantly higher among more educated adults than less educated, and has been consistently so for decades.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In 2019, 70% of college graduates support abortion being legal in all or most cases, as well as 60% of those with some college education, compared to 54% of those with a high school degree or less.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A January 2003 CBS News/*The New York Times* poll examined whether Americans thought abortion should be legal or not, and found variations in opinion which depended upon party affiliation and the region of the country.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The margin of error is +/– 4% for questions answered of the entire sample (overall figures) and may be higher for questions asked of subgroups (all other figures).
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A January 2026 poll by Pew Research found that support for legal abortion in the U.S. varies by race.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Polls indicates general support of legal abortion during the first trimester, although support drops dramatically for abortion during the second and third trimester.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Since the 2011 poll, support for legal abortion during the first trimester has declined.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] According to Gallup's long-time polling on abortion, the majority of Americans are neither strictly "pro-life" or "pro-choice"; it depends upon the circumstances of the pregnancy.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Gallup polling from 1996 to 2021 consistently reveals that when asked the question, "Do you think abortions should be legal under any circumstances, legal only under certain circumstances, or illegal in all circumstances?", Americans repeatedly answer "legal only under certain circumstances".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] According to the poll, in any given year 48–57% say legal only under certain circumstances, 21–34% say legal under any circumstances, and 13–19% illegal in all circumstances, with 1–7% having no opinion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] According to the aforementioned poll, Americans differ drastically based upon situation of the pregnancy, suggesting they do not support unconditional abortions.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Congress outlawed intact dilation and extraction when it passed the Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A Rasmussen Reports poll four days after the Supreme Court's opinion in *Gonzales v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Carhart* found that 40% of respondents "knew the ruling allowed states to place some restrictions on specific abortion procedures." Of those who knew of the decision, 56% agreed with the decision and 32% were opposed.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] An ABC poll from 2003 found that 62% of respondents thought "partial-birth abortion" should be illegal; a similar number of respondents wanted an exception "if it would prevent a serious threat to the woman's health".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Gallup has repeatedly queried the American public on this issue.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] After *Roe*, there was a national political realignment surrounding abortion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The abortion-rights movement in the United States initially emphasized the national policy benefits of abortion, such as smaller welfare expenses, slower population growth, and fewer illegitimate births.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The abortion-rights movement drew support from the population control movement, feminists, and environmentalists.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Anti-abortion advocates and civil-rights activists accused abortion-rights supporters of intending to control the population of racial minorities and the disabled, citing their ties to racial segregationists and eugenicist legal reformers.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The abortion-rights movement subsequently distanced from the population control movement, and responded by taking up choice-based and rights-oriented rhetoric similar to what was used in the *Roe* decision.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Opponents of abortion experienced a political shift.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Catholic Church and the Democratic Party supported an expansive welfare state, wanted to reduce rates of abortion through prenatal insurance and federally funded day care, and opposed abortion at the time of *Roe*.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Afterwards, the anti-abortion movement in the United States shifted more to Protestant faiths that saw abortion rights as part of a liberal-heavy agenda to fight against, and became part of the new Christian right.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Protestant influence helped make opposition to abortion part of the Republican Party's platform by the 1990s.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Republican-led states enacted laws to restrict abortion, including abortions earlier than *Casey*'s general standard of 24 weeks.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Into the 21st century, although members of both major U.S. political parties come down on either side of the issue, the Republican Party is often seen as being anti-abortion, since the official party platform opposes abortion and considers fetuses to have an inherent right to life.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Republicans for Choice represents the minority of that party.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In 2006, pollsters found that 9% of Republicans favor the availability of abortion in most circumstances.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Of Republican National Convention delegates in 2004, 13% believed that abortion should be generally available, and 38% believed that it should not be permitted.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The same poll showed that 17% of all Republican voters believed that abortion should be generally available to those who want it, while 38% believed that it should not be permitted.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Democratic Party platform considers abortion to be a woman's right.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Democrats for Life of America represents the minority of that party.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In 2006, pollsters found that 74% of Democrats favor the availability of abortion in most circumstances.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Of Democratic National Convention delegates in 2004, 75% believed that abortion should be generally available, and 2% believed that abortion should not be permitted.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The same poll showed that 49% of all Democratic voters believed that abortion should be generally available to those who want it, while 13% believed that it should not be permitted.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The position of U.S. third political parties and other U.S. minor political parties is diverse.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Green Party supports legal abortion as a woman's right.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Constitution Party is opposed to abortion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The issue of abortion has become deeply politicized.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In 2002, 84% of state Democratic platforms supported the right to having an abortion while 88% of state Republican platforms opposed it.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] This divergence also led to Christian right organizations like Christian Voice, Christian Coalition of America, and Moral Majority having an increasingly strong role in the Republican Party.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The policy was revoked by President Bill Clinton and subsequently reinstated by President George W.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] President Barack Obama overruled this policy by Executive Order on January 23, 2009, and it was reinstated on January 23, 2017, by President Donald Trump.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] On January 28, 2021, President Joe Biden signed a Presidential Memorandum that repealed the restoration of Mexico City policy and also called for the United States Department of Health and Human Services to "suspend, rescind or revoke" restrictions made to Title X.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] President Donald Trump reinstated the policy on January 24, 2025.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The risk of death due to legal abortion has fallen considerably since *Roe v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Wade* (1973) legalized it; this was due to increased physician skills, improved medical technology, and earlier termination of pregnancy.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] From 1940 through 1970, annual deaths of pregnant women during abortion fell from nearly 1,500 to a little over 100.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, the number of women who died in 1972 from illegal abortion was thirty-nine.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Roe effect is a hypothesis suggesting that since supporters of abortion rights cause the erosion of their own political base by having fewer children, the practice of abortion will eventually lead to the restriction or illegalization of abortion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The legalized abortion and crime effect is another controversial theory that posits legal abortion reduces crime because unwanted children are more likely to become criminals.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Since *Roe*, there have been numerous attempts to reverse the decision.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In the 2011 election season, Mississippi placed an amendment on the ballot that redefined how the state viewed abortion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The personhood amendment defined personhood as "every human being from the moment of fertilization, cloning or the functional equivalent thereof"; if passed, it would have been illegal to get an abortion in the state.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] On July 11, 2012, a Mississippi federal judge ordered an extension of his temporary order to allow the state's only abortion clinic to stay open.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The order was to stay in place until U.S.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] District Judge Daniel Porter Jordan III could review newly drafted rules on how the Mississippi Department of Health would administer a new abortion law.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The law in question came into effect on July 1, 2012.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Between 2008 and 2016, the Turnaway Study followed a group of 1,000 women, two of whom died after giving birth, for five years after they sought an abortion, and compared their health and socio-economic consequences of receiving an abortion or being denied one.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The study found that those who were provided with abortion performed better, and those who were denied one suffered negative consequences.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] *Scientific American* described it as landmark.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A follow-up Turnaway Study was confirmed to determinate the health and economic impact of *Roe* being overturned, which other scholars also analyzed.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Jackson Women's Health Organization* case, which confirmed the May 2022 leaks obtained by *Politico* and overruled *Roe* and *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The American Historical Association (AHA) and the Organization of American Historians (OAH) were among those who signed an *amici curiae* brief for *Dobbs*, and were cited, among others, by *Reason*, *Syracuse University News*, and *The Washington Post*.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Joined by at least 30 other academic and scholarly institutions, they condemned "the court's misinterpretation about the history of legalized abortion" and said it has "the potential to exacerbate historic injustices and deepen inequalities in our country".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In the wake of state abortion bans and restrictions in the United States, Americans have started traveling to Mexico for abortions, and Mexico has expressed a willingness to help.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Providers openly treat American travelers in several states where abortion remains technically illegal, such as Nuevo Leon, which neighbors Texas.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Following the Supreme Court ruling, abortion is being gradually legalized at the state level, and as of 2025 is legal during the first trimester (before the 13th week after implantation) in twenty states and Mexico City.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Although it is uncommon, women sometimes give birth in spite of an attempted abortion.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Reporting of live birth after attempted abortion may not be consistent from state to state, but 38 were recorded in one study in upstate New York in the two-and-a-half years before *Roe v.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] Baldwin served as a United States Senator from Georgia from 1799 to 1807.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] During his tenure, he served as President pro tempore of the United States Senate from 1801 to 1802.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] Abraham Baldwin was born in 1754 in Guilford in the Connecticut Colony into a large family, the son of Lucy (Dudley) and Michael Baldwin, a blacksmith, and descended from Elder John Strong.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] His half-brother, Henry Baldwin, was an Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] After attending Guilford Grammar School, Abraham Baldwin attended Yale College in nearby New Haven, Connecticut, where he was a member of the Linonian Society.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] Three years later after theological study, he was licensed as a Congregationalist minister.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] He also served as a tutor at the college.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] During the American Revolutionary War, he served as a chaplain in the Connecticut Contingent of the Continental Army.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] He did not see combat while with the Continental troops.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] Two years later at the conclusion of the war, Baldwin declined an offer from Yale's new president, Ezra Stiles, to become Professor of Divinity.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] Instead, he turned to the study of law and in 1783 was admitted to the Connecticut bar.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] Encouraged by his former commanding officer General Nathanael Greene, who had acquired the plantation at Mulberry Grove where Eli Whitney would later invent the cotton gin, Baldwin moved to Georgia.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] He was recruited by fellow Yale alumnus Governor Lyman Hall, another transplanted New Englander, to develop a state education plan.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] Baldwin was named the first president of the University of Georgia and became active in politics to build support for the university, which had not yet enrolled its first student.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] He was appointed as a delegate to the Congress of the Confederation and then to the Constitutional Convention; in September 1786 he was one of the state’s two signatories to the U.S.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] Baldwin remained president of the University of Georgia during its initial development phase until 1800.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] During this period, he also worked with the legislature on the college charter.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] In 1801, Franklin College, the University of Georgia's initial college, opened to students.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] Josiah Meigs was hired to succeed Baldwin as first acting president and oversee the inaugural class of students.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] The first buildings of the college were architecturally modeled on Baldwin's and Meigs's *alma mater* of Yale where they both had taught.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] Baldwin was elected to the Georgia Assembly, where he became very active, working to develop support for the college.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] He was able to mediate between the rougher frontiersmen, perhaps because of his childhood as the son of a blacksmith, and the aristocratic planter elite who dominated the coastal Lowcountry.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] He became one of the most prominent legislators, pushing significant measures such as the education bill through the sometimes split Georgia Assembly.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] He was elected as representative to the U.S.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] The Georgia legislature elected him as U.S.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] Senator in 1799 (this was the practice until popular election in 1913).
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] He served as president pro tempore of the United States Senate from December 1801 to December 1802.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] He was re-elected and served in office until his death.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/abraham-baldwin] On March 4, 1807, at age 52, Baldwin died while serving as a U.S. senator from Georgia.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] In the United States, an **act of Congress** is a statute passed by both the Senate and the House of Representatives of the United States Congress and signed into law by the president.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] Acts may apply only to individual entities (called private laws), or to the general public (public laws).
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] In the United States, acts of Congress are designated as either **public laws**, relating to the general public, or **private laws**, relating to specific institutions or individuals.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] Since 1957, all acts of Congress have been designated as "Public Law X–Y" or "Private Law X–Y".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] X is the number of the Congress and Y refers to the sequential order of the bill (when it was enacted).
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] 111–5 (American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009) was the fifth enacted public law of the 111th United States Congress.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] Public laws are also often abbreviated as Pub.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] When the legislation of those two kinds are proposed, it is called public bill and private bill respectively.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] The word "act", as used in the term "act of Congress", is a common, not a proper noun.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] The capitalization of the word "act" (especially when used standing alone to refer to an act mentioned earlier by its full name) is deprecated by some dictionaries and usage authorities.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] However, the Bluebook requires "Act" to be capitalized when referring to a specific legislative act.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] The United States Code capitalizes "act".
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] The term "act of Congress" is sometimes used in informal speech to indicate something for which getting permission is burdensome.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] Reconsideration by the Congress after a presidential veto during its session.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] A bill must receive a 2⁄3 majority vote in both houses to override a president's veto.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] The president promulgates acts of Congress made by the first two methods.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] If an act is made by the third method, the presiding officer of the house that last reconsidered the act promulgates it.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] Under the United States Constitution, if the president does not return a bill or resolution to Congress with objections before the time limit expires, then the bill automatically becomes an act.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] If the Congress is adjourned at the end of this period, then the bill dies and cannot be reconsidered (see pocket veto).
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] If the president rejects a bill or resolution while the Congress is in session, a two-thirds vote of both houses of Congress is needed for reconsideration to be successful.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] Promulgation in the sense of publishing and proclaiming the law is accomplished by the president, or the relevant presiding officer in the case of an overridden veto, delivering the act to the archivist of the United States.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] The archivist provides for its publication as a slip law and in the United States Statutes at Large after receiving the act.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] Thereafter, the changes are published in the United States Code.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] Through the process of judicial review, an act of Congress that violates the Constitution may be declared unconstitutional by the courts.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] A judicial declaration that an act of Congress is unconstitutional does not remove the act from the Statutes at Large or the United States Code; rather, it prevents the act from being enforced.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/act-of-congress] However, the act as published in annotated codes and legal databases is marked with annotations indicating that it is no longer good law.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/federal-government-of-the-united-states] The **federal government of the United States** (**U.S. federal government** or **U.S. government**) is the national government of the United States.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/federal-government-of-the-united-states] The United States federal government is composed of three distinct branches: legislative, executive, and judicial.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/federal-government-of-the-united-states] The powers of these three branches are defined and vested by the Constitution of the United States, which has been in effect since 1789.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/federal-government-of-the-united-states] The powers and duties of these branches are further defined by acts of Congress, including the creation of executive departments and courts subordinate to the Supreme Court of the United States.
[src:federal-government-of-the-united-states/federal-government-of-the-united-states] In the federal division of power, the federal government shares sovereignty with each of the 50 states in their respective territories.
